{"title_page": "AllyCAD", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=July 2008}}\n{{Infobox Software\n| name = AllyCAD\n| developer = Knowledge Base\n| latest release version = 3.6\n| latest release date = 2007\n| latest preview version = \n| latest preview date = \n| operating system = [[Microsoft Windows]]\n| language = \n| status = \n| genre = [[Computer-aided design|CAD]]\n| license = [[Proprietary software|Proprietary]]\n| website = {{URL|http://www.allycad.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''AllyCAD''' is a [[computer-aided design|CAD]] [[software application]] for [[2d computer graphics|2D]] and [[3d computer graphics|3D]] [[design]] and [[technical drawing|drafting]], developed and sold by Knowledge Base.<ref>http://knowbase.co.za/</ref> It is used primarily in [[Southern Africa]] and the [[UK]]<ref>[http://www.allycad.com/press.asp AllyCAD Showcases 2008 - 2012]</ref> in the [[Civil Engineering]] sector. AllyCAD is endorsed by the [[South African Institution of Civil Engineering]]{{citation needed|date=June 2012}} and the Engineering Council of South Africa{{citation needed|date=June 2012}} and incorporated into the Education Departments Engineering Graphics and Design curriculum across tertiary institutions in South Africa.{{Citation needed|date=July 2008}} They share the CAD market in [[South Africa]] primarily with [[AutoCAD]] and [[Caddie (CAD system)]].\n\n== History ==\n{{Refimprove|date=June 2012}}\nAllyCAD was originally developed by Paul Harper and was bought by Vincent Bester in February 1998. Vincent went on to develop The 'Civil Designer' civil engineering infrastructure design suite of software integrating AllyCAD as the central [[computer-aided design|CAD]] module. Elements of 'Stardust' and 'AllyCAD' were combined to form the Design Centre module, the Survey & Terrain and Roads modules came from Stardust, the Sewer and Storm modules were based on the original programs developed by Vincent. Since then the developer Knowledge Base distributes AllyCAD as a [[Computer software|stand-alone]] CAD software package.\n\n== Versions ==\nThe current version is AllyCAD 8.3<ref>https://www.civildesigner.com/version83/index.htm</ref><ref>http://www.allycad.com/news/2019/october.htm</ref>. There are four price versions of AllyCAD available<ref>https://www.allycad.com/shop.asp</ref>. All four have complete functionality but the drawing size is restricted in the low-cost versions. The entry level version (HOME edition<ref>https://www.allycad.com/homeversion.asp</ref>) can be downloaded at allycad.com. The full version, AllyCAD PRO, has no restrictions.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Comparison of CAD editors for AEC]]\n* [[Comparison of CAD editors for CAE]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.allycad.com/}}\n\n[[Category:Computer-aided design software]]\n\n\n{{CAD-software-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=July 2008}}\n{{Infobox Software\n| name = AllyCAD\n| developer = Knowledge Base\n| latest release version = 3.6\n| latest release date = 2007\n| latest preview version = \n| latest preview date = \n| operating system = [[Microsoft Windows]]\n| language = \n| status = \n| genre = [[Computer-aided design|CAD]]\n| license = [[Proprietary software|Proprietary]]\n| website = {{URL|http://www.allycad.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''AllyCAD''' is a [[computer-aided design|CAD]] [[software application]] for [[2d computer graphics|2D]] and [[3d computer graphics|3D]] [[design]] and [[technical drawing|drafting]], developed and sold by Knowledge Base.<ref>http://knowbase.co.za/</ref> It is used primarily in [[Southern Africa]] and the [[UK]]<ref>[http://www.allycad.com/press.asp AllyCAD Showcases 2008 - 2012]</ref> in the [[Civil Engineering]] sector. AllyCAD is endorsed by the [[South African Institution of Civil Engineering]]{{citation needed|date=June 2012}} and the Engineering Council of South Africa{{citation needed|date=June 2012}} and incorporated into the Education Departments Engineering Graphics and Design curriculum across tertiary institutions in South Africa.{{Citation needed|date=July 2008}} They share the CAD market in [[South Africa]] primarily with [[AutoCAD]] and [[Caddie (CAD system)]].\n\n== History ==\n{{Refimprove|date=June 2012}}\nAllyCAD was originally developed by Paul Harper and was bought by Vincent Bester in February 1998. Vincent went on to develop The 'Civil Designer' civil engineering infrastructure design suite of software integrating AllyCAD as the central [[computer-aided design|CAD]] module. Elements of 'Stardust' and 'AllyCAD' were combined to form the Design Centre module, the Survey & Terrain and Roads modules came from Stardust, the Sewer and Storm modules were based on the original programs developed by Vincent. Since then the developer Knowledge Base distributes AllyCAD as a [[Computer software|stand-alone]] CAD software package.\n\n== Versions ==\n{{Refimprove|date=June 2012}}\nThe current version is AllyCAD 8.3<ref>https://www.civildesigner.com/version83/index.htm</ref><ref>http://www.allycad.com/news/2019/october.htm</ref>. There are four price versions of AllyCAD available<ref>https://www.allycad.com/shop.asp</ref>. All four have complete functionality but the drawing size is restricted in the low-cost versions. The entry level version (HOME edition<ref>https://www.allycad.com/homeversion.asp</ref>) can be downloaded at allycad.com. The full version, AllyCAD PRO, has no restrictions.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Comparison of CAD editors for AEC]]\n* [[Comparison of CAD editors for CAE]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.allycad.com/}}\n\n[[Category:Computer-aided design software]]\n\n\n{{CAD-software-stub}}\n", "name_user": "ZengaONE", "label": "safe", "comment": "delete template code in section \"Version\"", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/AllyCAD"}
{"title_page": "Stoney (album)", "text_new": "{{short description|2016 debut studio album by Post Malone}}\n{{redirect|No Option|the song by DJ Snake featuring Burna Boy|Carte Blanche (DJ Snake album)}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name         = Stoney\n| type         = studio\n| artist       = [[Post Malone]]\n| cover        = Stoneyalbum.jpg\n| alt          = \n| released     = {{Start date|2016|12|09}}\n| recorded     = 2014\u20132016\n| venue        = \n| studio       = {{collapsible list|title={{nobold|Various}}|hlist=true|Kudo ([[Pacific Palisades, Los Angeles|Pacific Palisades, LA]])|Serenity West(Hollywood, CA)|Perfect Sound (Hollywood, CA)|The Gold House (Orlando, FL)|Electric Feel (Hollywood, CA)|Platinum Sound (New York City, NY)|The Mekanics ([[West Palm Beach, Florida|West Palm Beach, FL]])|[[Chalice Recording Studios|Chalice]] (Hollywood, CA)|Germano (New York City, NY)|The Grill (Oakland, CA)|Nightbird (Hollywood, CA)|[[Jim Henson Company Lot|Henson]] (Hollywood, CA)|[[The Cutting Room Studios|The Cutting Room]] (New York City, NY)}}\n| genre        =\n* [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hiphopdx.com/reviews/id.2882/title.review-post-malone-does-hip-hop-his-way-on-stoney|title=Post Malone Stoney Album Review|last=Diep|first=Eric|date=December 18, 2016|website=[[HipHopDX]]|access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.albumoftheyear.org/album/64916-post-malone-stoney.php|title=Post Malone - Stoney - Reviews|website=[[Album of the Year (website)|AOTY]]|access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n| length       = Standard: 50:40 Deluxe: 68:14\n| label        = [[Republic Records|Republic]]\n| producer     = {{hlist|Cashio {{small|([[Executive producer#Music|exec.]])}}|Charlie Handsome {{small|(exec.)}}|Dre London {{small|(exec.)}}|[[FKi 1st]] {{small|(exec.)}}|Rex Kudo {{small|(exec.)}}|[[Andrew Watt (musician)|Andrew Watt]]|[[DJ Mustard]]|Foreign Teck|[[Frank Dukes]]|[[Illangelo]]|Justin Mosley|[[Leon Thomas III]]|[[Louis Bell]]|[[Metro Boomin]]|[[Pharrell Williams]]|[[Jahphet Landis|Roofeeo]]|Twice as Nice|[[Vinylz]]}}\n| prev_title   = [[August 26th (mixtape)|August 26th]]\n| prev_year    = 2016\n| next_title   = [[Beerbongs & Bentleys]]\n| next_year    = 2018\n| misc         = {{Singles\n| name        = Stoney\n| type        = studio\n| single1     = [[White Iverson]]\n| single1date = August 14, 2015\n| single2     = [[Too Young (Post Malone song)|Too Young]]\n| single2date = October 9, 2015\n| single3     = [[Go Flex]]\n| single3date = April 21, 2016\n| single4     = [[Deja Vu (Post Malone song)|Deja Vu]]\n| single4date = September 9, 2016\n| single5     = [[Congratulations (Post Malone song)|Congratulations]]\n| single5date = January 31, 2017\n| single6     = [[I Fall Apart]]\n| single6date = October 17, 2017\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Stoney''''' is the debut studio album by American singer and rapper [[Post Malone]]. It was released on December 9, 2016, by [[Republic Records]]. The album features [[guest appearance]]s from [[Justin Bieber]], [[Kehlani]], [[Quavo]], and [[2 Chainz]]. The production on the album was handled by [[DJ Mustard]], [[Metro Boomin]], [[Vinylz]], [[Frank Dukes]], [[Illangelo]], Charlie Handsome, Rex Kudo, Foreign Teck, and [[Pharrell Williams]], among others.\n\n''Stoney'' debuted at number six on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] and later peaked at number four. \"[[Congratulations (Post Malone song)|Congratulations]]\" was first released as the album's first [[promotional single]] on November 4, 2016. The single was certified [[RIAA certification|Diamond]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA) and was Post's biggest [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] hit at the time. ''Stoney'' was certified [[RIAA certification|triple platinum]] by the Recording Industry Association of America (RIAA) and [[BPI certification|platinum]] by the [[British Phonographic Industry]] (BPI).\n\n==Background==\nOn August 14, 2015, Post Malone released his debut [[Single (music)|single]], \"[[White Iverson]]\". The single became his breakthrough song. Due to his success with that single, Malone collaborated with a number of prominent rappers such as Petal Aggression, [[Young Thug]] and [[Kanye West]], among others.<ref>{{cite web|last=Akubuilo|first=Nneoma|date=February 12, 2016|url=http://smashd.co/yeezy-season-3/|title=Yeezy Season 3|access-date=February 18, 2016|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160301123451/http://smashd.co/yeezy-season-3/|archive-date=March 1, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/magazine-feature/6762300/interview-post-malone-kanye-west|title=Rapper Post Malone on Collaborating With Kanye West: 'It Was the Scariest Experience Ever'|website=Billboard|access-date=April 29, 2016}}</ref> Malone and Canadian singer-songwriter [[Justin Bieber]] verged into this friendship, when Bieber made Malone as one of the [[opening act|opening acts]] for his [[Purpose World Tour]] to support the release of his fourth studio album, ''[[Purpose (Justin Bieber album)|Purpose]]'' (2015).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.freep.com/picture-gallery/entertainment/music/2016/04/25/justin-bieber-at-the-palace/83530406/|title=Justin Bieber at the Palace|website=Detroit Free Press|access-date=April 29, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn June 9, 2016, Malone made his national television debut on ''[[Jimmy Kimmel Live!]]'', performing the song, \"[[Go Flex]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2016/06/09/post-malone-performs-go-flex-on-jimmy-kimmel-live/|title=Post Malone Performs 'Go Flex' on 'Jimmy Kimmel Live!'|publisher=|accessdate=July 1, 2016}}</ref> In June 2016, ''[[XXL (magazine)|XXL]]'' editor-in chief Vanessa Satten, revealed that Malone was considered to be on ''XXL''{{'}}s \"2016's Freshmen Class\" magazine cover, however, she was \"told by his camp that he wasn't paying attention to hip hop so much. He was going into more of a [[Rock music|rock]] / [[Pop music|pop]] / [[Country music|country]] direction.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/post-malone-going-in-rock-pop-country-direction-news.22223.html|title=Post Malone Going In \"Rock/Pop/Country Direction\"|publisher=|accessdate=July 1, 2016}}</ref> Malone denied these claims, saying: \"My love of music should never be questioned... I shouldn't be chastised for expressing myself in whichever way I see fit.\" He went on to explain that his latest mixtape, as well as his upcoming album are both hip hop: \"I have a hip-hop album coming out in August... I made a HIP HOP mixtape promoting my HIP HOP album.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/post-malone-responds-to-xxl-claiming-hes-not-focused-on-hip-hop-news.22293.html|title=Post Malone Responds To XXL Claiming He's Not Focused on Hip-Hop|publisher=|accessdate=July 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2016, in preparation for the release of ''Stoney'', Malone released his debut [[mixtape]], titled ''[[August 26th (mixtape)|August 26th]]''. The name was a reference to the original release date for ''Stoney'', however, the album suffered numerous delays.\n\n==Singles==\nThe album's lead [[Single (music)|single]], \"[[White Iverson]]\", was released on August 14, 2015. The song was produced by Post Malone himself, alongside Rex Kudo. The song peaked at number 14 on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] and was certified [[RIAA certification|five-times platinum]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA).\n\nThe album's second single, \"[[Too Young (Post Malone song)|Too Young]]\", was released on October 9, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/post-malone-too-young-prod-by-fki-and-the-mekanics-new-song.1964147.html|title=Post Malone - Too Young (Prod. By FKi 1st & The MeKanics) - Stream [New Song]|author=|date=|work=hotnewhiphop.com|accessdate=November 14, 2016}}</ref> The song was produced by Foreign Teck and Justin Mosely. The song was later certified platinum by the Recording Industry Association of America (RIAA) in 2017.\n\nThe album's third single, \"[[Go Flex]]\", was released on April 21, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/post-malone-go-flex-new-song.1969494.html|title=Post Malone \u2013 Go Flex \u2013 Stream [New Song]|author=|date=|work=hotnewhiphop.com|accessdate=November 14, 2016}}</ref> The song was produced by Charlie Handsome and Rex Kudo. The song was certified three-times platinum by the Recording Industry Association of America (RIAA).\n \nThe album's fourth single, \"[[Deja Vu (Post Malone song)|Deja Vu]]\", was released on September 9, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/deja-vu-feat.-justin-bieber/id1150088897|title=Deja Vu (feat. Justin Bieber) - Single by Post Malone on Apple Music - iTunes|accessdate=September 8, 2016}}</ref> The song features a [[guest appearance]] from Canadian singer-songwriter [[Justin Bieber]], while the production was handled by [[Frank Dukes]] and [[Vinylz]]. The song is certified platinum by the Recording Industry Association of America (RIAA).\n\n\"[[Congratulations (Post Malone song)|Congratulations]]\" was first released as the album's first [[promotional single]] on November 4, 2016.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2016/11/post-malone-new-song-congratulations-feat-quavo|title=Post Malone Grabs Quavo for \"Congratulations\"|author=|date=|work=complex.com|accessdate=November 14, 2016}}</ref> It was later sent to rhythmic radio as the album's fifth official single. The song features a guest appearance from [[Southern hip hop]] rapper [[Quavo]], while the production was handled by [[Metro Boomin]] and Frank Dukes, with additional production by Louis Bell. The song was certified diamond by the Recording Industry Association of America (RIAA) and became his biggest and first international hit.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/post-malones-congratulations-goes-platinum-shares-cover-art-for-beerbongs-and-bentleys-news.30434.html|title=Post Malone's \"Congratulations\" Goes Platinum; Shares Cover Art For \"Beerbongs & Bentleys\"|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nA live performance of \"[[I Fall Apart]]\" received significant attention on social media and sales for the song sent it into the top 20 on [[iTunes]]. Republic promptly sent the song to rhythmic radio as the album's sixth and final single, on October 17, 2017, despite \"[[Rockstar (Post Malone song)|Rockstar]]\" having recently been released as a single from his then-upcoming [[Beerbongs & Bentleys|second studio album]].<ref name=\"Future Rhythmic Radio Releases\">{{citeweb|url=https://www.allaccess.com/top40-rhythmic/future-releases|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171003191743/https://www.allaccess.com/top40-rhythmic/future-releases|title=Top 40 Rhythmic Future Releases|publisher=All Access|archive-date=October 3, 2017}}</ref> As a single, \"I Fall Apart\" went on to peak at number 16 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100.\n\n===Promotional singles===\nThe album's first promotional single, \"Patient\", was released on November 18, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/rap-music/new-music/2016/11/post-malone-vents-on-patient/|title=Post Malone Vents On 'Patient'|publisher=XXL|date=November 18, 2016|accessdate=November 20, 2016}}</ref> The song was produced by Louis Bell.\n\nThe album's second promotional single, \"Leave\", was released on December 2, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/rap-music/new-music/2016/12/post-malone-keeps-the-momentum-going-with-leave/|title=Post Malone Keeps Up The Momentum With 'Leave'|publisher=XXL|date=December 2, 2016|accessdate=December 3, 2016}}</ref> The song was produced by Rex Kudo, Cashio and Charlie Handsome.\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|2|5}}<ref name=allmusic>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/stoney-mw0002997061|title=Stoney \u2013 Post Malone|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|last=Yeung|first=Neil Z.|accessdate=December 9, 2016}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[Exclaim!]]''\n| rev2score = 6/10<ref name=exclaim>{{cite web|url=http://exclaim.ca/music/article/post_malone-stoney|title=Post Malone: Stoney|work=[[Exclaim!]]|last=Zoledziowski|first=Anya|date=December 13, 2016|accessdate=December 21, 2016}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[HipHopDX]]''\n| rev3score = 3.7/5<ref name=\"HipHopDX\">{{cite web|url=http://hiphopdx.com/reviews/id.2882/title.review-post-malone-does-hip-hop-his-way-on-stoney|title=Review: Post Malone Does Hip Hop His Way On \"Stoney\"|work=[[HipHopDX]]|last=Diep|first=Eric|date=December 18, 2016|accessdate=December 2, 2019}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[Newsday]]''\n| rev4score =  B<ref name=newsday>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsday.com/entertainment/music/stoney-review-post-malone-s-promising-yet-lacking-debut-1.12718444|title='Stoney' review: Post Malone's promising -- yet lacking -- debut|work=[[Newsday]]|last=Gamboa|first=Glenn|date=December 9, 2016|accessdate=December 11, 2016}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev5score = 4.5/10<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/22686-stoney/|title=Post Malone: Stoney|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|last=Ramirez|first=Matthew|date=December 15, 2016|accessdate=December 2, 2019}}</ref>\n}}\nComparing the album to Malone's debut single, \"[[White Iverson]]\", Glenn Gamboa of ''[[Newsday]]'' wrote that he \"follows through with that style on ''Stoney'', but it generally pales in comparison to the inventiveness and the surprise of that track.\"<ref name=newsday/> Neil Z. Yeung of [[AllMusic]] commented that ''Stoney'' is \"competent and listenable, but many others have tread this same path already. Post Malone has a way to go before standing out with his own unique voice, but there are signs on ''Stoney'' that it could happen.\"<ref name=allmusic/>\n\n===Accolades===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Award\n! scope=\"col\" | Year{{efn|Indicates the year of ceremony. Each year is linked to the article about the awards held that year, wherever possible.}}\n! scope=\"col\" | Category\n! scope=\"col\" | Result\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\"| {{Abbr|Ref.|References}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"2\"| [[Billboard Music Awards|''Billboard'' Music Awards]]\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[2018 Billboard Music Awards|2018]]\n| [[Billboard Music Award for Top Rap Album|Top Rap Album]]\n| {{nominated}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"2\"|<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/bbma/8456842/billboard-music-awards-2018-winners-list-bbmas |title=Here Are All the Winners From the 2018 Billboard Music Awards|date=May 20, 2018|work=Billboard|access-date=May 20, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Billboard Music Award for Top Billboard 200 Album|Top Billboard 200 Album]]\n| {{nominated}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Juno Awards]]\n| [[Juno Awards of 2018|2018]]\n| [[Juno Award for International Album of the Year|International Album of the Year]]\n| {{nominated}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{Cite web|last1=Lau|first1=Melody|title=The 2018 Juno nominations, by the numbers {{!}} CBC Music|url=http://www.cbc.ca/music/junos/news/the-2018-juno-nominations-by-the-numbers-1.4522937 |publisher=CBC|access-date=February 11, 2018|date=February 9, 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180209000932/http://www.cbc.ca/music/junos/news/the-2018-juno-nominations-by-the-numbers-1.4522937|archive-date=February 9, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n{{end}}\n\n==Commercial performance==\n''Stoney'' debuted at number six on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] with 58,000 [[album-equivalent unit]]s, of which 19,000 were pure album sales.<ref name=\"Billboard debut\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/7625536/j-cole-fourth-no-1-billboard-200|title=J. Cole Scores His Fourth No. 1 Album on Billboard 200 Chart, With Third-Largest Debut of 2016|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|last=Caulfield|first=Keith|date=December 19, 2016|accessdate=December 20, 2016}}</ref> In its second week, the album dropped to number 23 on the chart, selling an additional 30,000 units.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hiphopdx.com/news/id.41812/title.hip-hop-album-sales-kid-cudi-gucci-mane-debut-in-top-20|title=Hip Hop Album Sales: Kid Cudi & Gucci Mane Debut In Top 20|work=HipHopDX}}</ref> On June 6, 2018, the album was certified [[RIAA certification|three-times platinum]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA) for combined sales and album-equivalent units of over three million units.<ref name=RIAA/> On the week of October 28, 2017, the album peaked at number four on the US ''Billboard'' 200.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/billboard-200/2017-10-28|title=Top Billboard 200|work=Billboard|accessdate=November 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\nBy the end of 2017, ''Stoney'' had sold 1,564,000 album-equivalent units with 128,000 being pure sales.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8085932/ed-sheeran-divide-nielsen-music-top-album-2017|title=Ed Sheeran's 'Divide' Is Nielsen Music's Top Album of 2017 in U.S.|last=Caulfield|first=Keith|date=January 3, 2018|work=|access-date=August 28, 2019}}</ref> By September 2018, ''Stoney'' had sold 1,044,000 album-equivalent units that year.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://hitsdailydouble.com/news&id=313319|title=HITS Daily Double: Rumor Mill - YEAR-TO-DATE ALBUMS|work=HITS Daily Double|access-date=September 10, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\nCredits adapted from the album's liner notes, [[Tidal (service)|Tidal]] and [[Broadcast Music, Inc.|BMI]].<ref name=LN>{{cite AV media notes|title=Stoney|type=CD liner notes|others=[[Post Malone]]|publisher=[[Republic Records]]|year=2016|id=26163-9}}</ref><ref name=Tidal>{{cite web|url=https://listen.tidal.com/album/67803355|title=Stoney (Deluxe) / Post Malone|publisher=[[Tidal (service)|Tidal]]|accessdate=April 26, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://repertoire.bmi.com/Catalog.aspx?detail=writerid&page=1&fromrow=1&torow=25&keyid=1676395&subid=0|title=BMI {{!}} Repertoire Search|publisher=[[Broadcast Music, Inc.|BMI]]|accessdate=April 26, 2018|at=Select \"TITLE\", type \"Song\" in the search engine, and click \"Search\".}}</ref>\n\n{{Track listing\n| headline = ''Stoney'' {{nobold|\u2013 Standard edition}}<ref name=iTunes>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/stoney/1170719698|title=Stoney by Post Malone|publisher=[[iTunes Store]] (US)|accessdate=April 26, 2018}}</ref>\n| extra_column = Producer(s)\n| total_length = 50:40\n| title1 = Broken Whiskey Glass\n| writer1 = {{hlist|[[Post Malone|Austin Post]]|[[FKi 1st|Trocon Roberts]]|Masamune Kudo|Idan Kalai}}\n| extra1 = {{hlist|[[FKi 1st]]|Rex Kudo}}\n| length1 = 3:53\n| title2 = Big Lie\n| writer2 = {{hlist|Post|[[DJ Mustard|Dijon McFarlane]]|Nicholas Audino|Lewis Hughes|Te Whiti Warbrick|[[Louis Bell]]|Carl Rosen}}\n| extra2 = {{hlist|[[DJ Mustard]]|Twice as Nice{{ref|a|[a]}}|Bell{{ref|b|[b]}}}}\n| length2 = 3:27\n| title3 = [[Deja Vu (Post Malone song)|Deja Vu]]\n| note3 = featuring [[Justin Bieber]]\n| writer3 = {{hlist|Post|[[Justin Bieber]]|[[Frank Dukes|Adam Feeney]]|[[Vinylz|Anderson Hernandez]]|[[BadBadNotGood|Matthew Tavares]]|Kaan Gunesberk|Julian Swirsky|Bell}}\n| extra3 = {{hlist|[[Frank Dukes]]|[[Vinylz]]}}\n| length3 = 3:54\n| title4 = No Option\n| writer4 = {{hlist|Post|Bieber| Kalai|Roberts|Bell|Michael Hancock|Michael McGinnis|Christopher Rude}}\n| extra4 = {{hlist|Cashio|FKi 1st|Bell{{ref|b|[b]}}}}\n| length4 = 2:59\n| title5 = Cold\n| writer5 = {{hlist|Post|Feeney|Roberts}}\n| extra5 = {{hlist|FKi 1st|Frank Dukes|Bell{{ref|b|[b]}}}}\n| length5 = 4:28\n| title6 = [[White Iverson]]\n| writer6 = {{hlist|Post|Roberts|Kudo|Dre London}}\n| extra6 = {{hlist|[[Post Malone]]|Rex Kudo{{ref|a|[a]}}}}\n| length6 = 4:16\n| title7 = [[I Fall Apart]]\n| writer7 = {{hlist|Post|[[Illangelo|Carlo Montagnese]]|William Walsh}}\n| extra7 = [[Illangelo]]\n| length7 = 3:43\n| title8 = Patient\n| writer8 = {{hlist|Post|Bell|Rosen}}\n| extra8 = Bell\n| length8 = 3:14\n| title9 = [[Go Flex]]\n| writer9 = {{hlist|Post|Ryan Vojtesak|Kudo|Kalai}}\n| extra9 = {{hlist|Charlie Handsome|Rex Kudo}}\n| length9 = 2:59\n| title10 = Feel\n| note10 = featuring [[Kehlani]]\n| writer10 = {{hlist|Post|[[Kehlani|Kehlani Parrish]]|Kalai|Vojtesak|Roberts}}\n| extra10 = {{hlist|Cashio|Charlie Handsome|FKi 1st}}\n| length10 = 3:17\n| title11 = [[Too Young (Post Malone song)|Too Young]]\n| writer11 = {{hlist|Post|Michael Hernandez|Justin Mosley}}\n| extra11 = {{hlist|Foreign Teck|Mosley}}\n| length11 = 3:57\n| title12 = [[Congratulations (Post Malone song)|Congratulations]]\n| note12 = featuring [[Quavo]]\n| writer12 = {{hlist|Post|[[Quavo|Quavious Marshall]]|[[Metro Boomin|Leland Wayne]]|Feeney|Bell}}\n| extra12 = {{hlist|[[Metro Boomin]]|Frank Dukes|Bell{{ref|b|[b]}}}}\n| length12 = 3:40\n| title13 = Up There\n| writer13 = {{hlist|Post|[[Pharrell Williams]]|Bell|Rosen}}\n| extra13 = {{hlist|Williams|Bell{{ref|b|[b]}}}}\n| length13 = 3:14\n| title14 = Yours Truly, Austin Post\n| writer14 = {{hlist|Post|Bell|[[Jahphet Landis]]|[[Leon Thomas III|Leon Thomas]]}}\n| extra14 = {{hlist|Bell|[[Jahphet Landis|Roofeeo]]|Thomas}}\n| length14 = 3:39\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| headline = ''Stoney'' {{nobold|\u2013 Deluxe edition (bonus tracks)}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/stoney-deluxe/1170699981|title=Stoney (Deluxe) by Post Malone|publisher=iTunes Store (US)|accessdate=April 26, 2018}}</ref>\n| collapsed = yes\n| extra_column = Producer(s)\n| total_length = 68:14\n| title15 = Leave\n| writer15 = {{hlist|Post|Kudo|Vojtesak|Kalai}}\n| extra15 = {{hlist|Charlie Handsome|Rex Kudo|Cashio}}\n| length15 = 5:24\n| title16 = Hit This Hard\n| writer16 = {{hlist|Post|Roberts|Montagnese|Walsh}}\n| extra16 = Illangelo\n| length16 = 4:09\n| title17 = Money Made Me Do It\n| note17 = featuring [[2 Chainz]]\n| writer17 = {{hlist|Post|[[2 Chainz|Tauheed Epps]]|Roberts}}\n| extra17 = {{hlist|FKi 1st|Bell{{ref|b|[b]}}}}\n| length17 = 3:44\n| title18 = Feeling Whitney\n| writer18 = {{hlist|Post|[[Andrew Watt (musician)|Andrew Watt]]}}\n| extra18 = {{hlist|Watt|Bell{{ref|a|[a]}}}}\n| length18 = 4:17\n}}\n\n'''Notes'''\n* {{sup|{{note|a|[a]}}}} signifies a co-[[Record producer|producer]]\n* {{sup|{{note|b|[b]}}}} signifies a vocal producer\n* \"Deja Vu\" features background vocals from Kaan Gunesberk\n* \"Cold\" features background vocals from [[River Tiber (musician)|River Tiber]]\n* \"Go Flex\" features background vocals from Charlie Handsome and Peter Lee Johnson\n* \"Leave\" features background vocals from Peter Lee Johnson\n* \"Feeling Whitney\" features background vocals from [[Andrew Watt (musician)|Andrew Watt]] and Josh Gudwin\n\n'''Sample credits'''\n* \"Big Lie\" contains an interpolation from \"Clouds\", as performed by [[Gigi Masin]].\n* \"No Option\" contains excerpts from \"Levitate\", written by Michael Hancock, Michael McGinnis, and Christopher Rude, as performed by Viigo.\n\n==Personnel==\nCredits adapted from the album's liner notes and Tidal.<ref name=LN/><ref name=Tidal/>\n\n'''Musicians'''\n{{div col}}\n* [[Post Malone|Austin Post]] \u2013 guitars {{small|(tracks 1, 15, 18)}}\n* Peter Lee Johnson \u2013 strings {{small|(tracks 1, 9, 15)}}, guitars {{small|(tracks 9, 15)}}\n* [[BadBadNotGood|Matthew Tavares]] \u2013 guitar, bass, keyboards {{small|(track 3)}}\n* [[Frank Dukes|Adam Feeney]] \u2013 percussion {{small|(track 3)}}\n* [[Vinylz|Anderson Hernandez]] \u2013 percussion {{small|(track 3)}}\n* [[Andrew Watt (musician)|Andrew Watt]] \u2013 guitar {{small|(tracks 4, 18)}}, bass, string arrangement {{small|(track 18)}}\n* Charlie Handsome \u2013 drums {{small|(track 9, 10)}}, guitar {{small|(track 9)}}, keyboards {{small|(track 10)}}, bass {{small|(track 15)}}\n* Rex Kudo \u2013 drums {{small|(tracks 9, 15)}}\n* Idan Kalai \u2013 bass, drums, keyboards {{small|(track 10)}}\n* [[Spymob|Brent Paschke]] \u2013 electric guitars {{small|(track 13)}}\n* [[Leon Thomas III|Leon Thomas]] \u2013 guitars, bass {{small|(track 14)}}\n* Khari Mateen \u2013 cello {{small|(track 18)}}\n* [[Jessy Greene]] \u2013 cello {{small|(track 18)}}, violin {{small|(track 18)}}\n{{div col end}}\n\n'''Technical'''\n{{div col}}\n* Rex Kudo \u2013 recording {{small|(tracks 1, 6, 15)}}\n* Idan Kalai \u2013 recording {{small|(tracks 1, 6, 15)}}\n* [[Andrew Maury]] \u2013 mixing {{small|(tracks 1, 15)}}\n* [[Mike Bozzi]] \u2013 mastering {{small|(tracks 1\u20135, 7\u201310, 12\u201317)}}\n* [[Louis Bell]] \u2013 recording {{small|(tracks 2\u20135, 8, 12, 14)}}\n* Alex Pavone \u2013 recording assistance {{small|(tracks 2\u20136, 14, 16)}}\n* [[Manny Marroquin]] \u2013 mixing {{small|(tracks 2\u20135, 7\u201314, 16, 17)}}\n* Chris Galland \u2013 mixing assistance {{small|(tracks 2\u20135, 7\u201314, 16, 17)}}\n* Robin Florent \u2013 mixing assistance {{small|(tracks 2\u20135, 7\u201314, 16, 17)}}\n* Scott Desmarais \u2013 mixing assistance {{small|(tracks 2\u20135, 7\u201314, 16, 17)}}\n* Jeff Jackson \u2013 mixing assistance {{small|(tracks 2\u20135, 7, 8, 10, 12\u201314, 16, 17)}}\n* [[Illangelo]] \u2013 recording {{small|(tracks 7, 16)}}\n* Ike Schultz \u2013 mixing assistance {{small|(tracks 9, 11)}}\n* Big Bass Brian - mastering {{small|(track 11)}}\n* Adam Feeney \u2013 recording {{small|(track 12)}}\n* Andrew Coleman \u2013 recording {{small|(track 13)}}\n* Dave Rowland \u2013 recording {{small|(track 13)}}\n* Mike Larson \u2013 additional recording {{small|(track 13)}}\n* David Kim \u2013 recording assistance {{small|(track 13)}}\n* Josh Gudwin \u2013 recording {{small|(track 18)}}, mixing {{small|(track 18)}}\n* Nicolas Essig \u2013 recording {{small|(track 18)}}\n{{div col end}}\n\n'''Additional personnel'''\n{{div col}}\n* Dre London \u2013 management\n* [[Rob Stevenson]] \u2013 A&R\n* Tyler Arnold \u2013 A&R\n* Jim Roppo \u2013 marketing\n* Marleny Dominguez \u2013