{"title_page": "Tom Moore (fundraiser)", "text_new": "<noinclude>{{User:RMCD bot/subject notice|1=Tom's 100th Birthday Walk For The NHS|2=Talk:Tom Moore (fundraiser)#Requested move 22 April 2020 }}\n</noinclude>{{short description|British Army Officer and fundraiser}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix   = [[Captain (British Army and Royal Marines)|Captain]]\n| name               = Tom Moore\n| image              = Captain Tom Moore fundraising walk.jpg\n| image_size         = \n| caption            = Moore during his fund-raising walk. He is wearing the [[1939\u20131945 Star]], [[Burma Star]], and [[War Medal 1939\u20131945]].\n| alt                = Moore wearing a blazer with regimental badge, regimental tie and three medals\n| birth_name         = Thomas Moore\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1920|4|30|df=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[Keighley]], [[West Riding of Yorkshire]], England\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| death_cause        = \n| education          = \n| alma mater         = \n| occupation         = {{Plainlist|\n* Army officer\n* Managing director \n}}\n| title              = \n| term               = \n| predecessor        = \n| successor          = \n| known_for          = {{Plainlist|\n* Second World War veteran\n* 2020 fundraising walk\n}}\n| alma_mater         = [[Keighley Grammar School]], West Yorkshire\n| boards             = \n| spouse             = \n| children           = 2\n| parents            = \n| relations          = \n| website            = {{URL|https://www.justgiving.com/fundraising/tomswalkforthenhs|Tom's Walk for the NHS (JustGiving)}}\n| module = {{Infobox military person |embed=yes\n   | allegiance  = {{GBR}}\n   |branch       = {{flagicon image|Flag of the British Army (1938-present).png}} [[British Army]]\n   |serviceyears = 1939\u20131946\n   |rank         = [[Captain (British Army and Royal Marines)|Captain]]\n   |unit         = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Duke of Wellington's Regiment]]\n* [[145th Regiment Royal Armoured Corps]]\n* [[146th Regiment Royal Armoured Corps]]\n}}\n   |commands     = \n   |battles           = {{tree list}}\n*[[World War II|Second World War]]\n**[[Burma campaign 1944\u201345|Burma Campaign]]\n***[[Battle of Ramree Island]]\n   |awards = \n  }}\n}}\n'''Thomas Moore''' (born 30 April 1920), informally known as '''Captain Tom''', is a former [[British Army]] officer known for his philanthropic work. Moore served in India and the [[Burma campaign]] during the [[Second World War]]. He later became an instructor in [[armoured warfare]]. After the war, he worked as managing director of a concrete company and was an avid motorcycle racer. On 6 April 2020, at the age of 99, he began to walk around his garden in aid of [[NHS Charities Together]] during the [[COVID-19 pandemic in the United Kingdom|COVID-19 pandemic]], with the goal of raising \u00a31,000 by his hundredth birthday. By 22 April he had raised over \u00a328.1<!-- please update the figure in two places and the date/timestamp -->&nbsp;million.\n\n== Early life and family ==\n\nMoore was born to Wilfred, one of a family of builders, in [[Keighley]], in the former [[West Riding of Yorkshire]], on 30 April 1920 and was raised in the town.<ref name=\"Brown\">{{cite news |last1=Brown |first1=Faye |title=The story behind the 99-year-old legend who raised \u00a314m for the NHS |url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/04/16/tom-moore-story-behind-14000000-nhs-legend-12565964/ |accessdate=17 April 2020 |work=Metro |date=16 April 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.strayfm.com/news/local-news/3082429/coronavirus-veteran-from-keighley-raises-over-2-million-for-nhs/|title=Coronavirus: Veteran from Keighley raises over \u00a32 MILLION for NHS|date=14 April 2020|website=Stray FM|accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2020/apr/14/war-veteran-99-raises-2m-for-nhs-by-walking-lengths-of-back-garden|title=War veteran, 99, raises \u00a36m for NHS by walking lengths of back garden|first=Jessica|last=Murray|date=15 April 2020|accessdate=15 April 2020|work=The Guardian}}</ref> He was educated at [[Keighley Grammar School]] and completed an apprenticeship in [[civil engineering]].<ref name=\"Nicholls\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2020/04/14/second-world-war-veteran-raises-2-million-nhs/ |title=Second World War veteran raises more than \u00a33m for NHS |first=Dominic |last=Nicholls |date=14 April 2020 |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=The Telegraph}}</ref>\n\n== Military career ==\n\nMoore  enlisted in the [[Duke of Wellington's Regiment#8th Battalion|8th Battalion, Duke of Wellington's Regiment]] (8&nbsp;DWR) at the beginning of the [[Second World War]], stationed in [[Cornwall]].<ref name=\"Brown\" /> He was selected for officer training in 1940,<ref name=\"Nicholls\" />  and attended an Officer Cadet Training Unit before being commissioned as a [[second lieutenant#United Kingdom & other Commonwealth countries|second lieutenant]] on 28&nbsp;June 1941.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=35218|date=11 July 1941|page=4057|supp=y}}</ref>\n\nMoore became a member of the [[Royal Armoured Corps]] on 22 October 1941 when his battalion, the 8&nbsp;DWR, became an armoured unit, designated as the [[145th Regiment Royal Armoured Corps]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=35740|date=9 October 1942|page=4432|supp=y}}</ref><ref name=\"Nicholls\"/> Later he was transferred to the 9th&nbsp;Battalion (9&nbsp;DWR) in India, which had also been redesignated as the [[146th Regiment Royal Armoured Corps]]. He was initially posted to [[Bombay]] and subsequently to [[Calcutta]].<ref name=\"Brown\" /> His regiment were equipped with [[M3 Lee]] tanks and participated in the [[Battle of Ramree Island]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Whiting |first1=Charles |last2=Taylor |first2=Eric |date=2008 |title=The Fighting Tykes: An Informal History of the Yorkshire Regiments in the Second World War |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=9kt-AwAAQBAJ&pg=PA132 |publisher=Pen & Sword Military |page=132 |isbn=978-1844156450}}</ref> He was promoted to war-substantive [[Lieutenant (British Army and Royal Marines)|lieutenant]] on 1&nbsp;October 1942 and to temporary [[Captain (British Army and Royal Marines)|captain]] on 11&nbsp;October 1944.<ref>{{cite book |date=1946 |title=The Quarterly Army List (August 1946 \u2013 Part I) |location=London |publisher=HM Stationery Office |isbn= |pages=385a |url=https://archive.org/details/armylistaugpart121946grea/page/398/mode/2up|archive-url=|archive-date=}}</ref>\n\nHe served in [[Arakan]] in western Burma and afterward in [[Sumatra]] after the [[Surrender of Japan|Japanese surrender]],<ref name=\"Nicholls\"/><ref name=\"BBC-52278746\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-beds-bucks-herts-52278746 |title=Army veteran, 99, raises \u00a34m for 'humbled' NHS |date=15 April 2020 |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=BBC News}}</ref> by which time he had risen to the rank of captain.<ref name=\"Nicholls\" /><ref name=\"BBC-52278746\"/> On his return to Britain he served as an instructor at the Armoured Fighting Vehicle School in [[Bovington Camp|Bovington]], Dorset.<ref name=\"Nicholls\"/><ref name=\"BBC-52278746\"/>\n\n=== Decorations ===\n\nFor his war service, Moore was awarded three medals:<ref name=\"ES\">{{cite news |title=War veteran, 99, hits \u00a314m for NHS as Hancock calls him an inspiration |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/uk/war-veteran-tom-moore-matt-hancock-9-million-nhs-a4415496.html |accessdate=17 April 2020 |work=Evening Standard |date=16 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\n*[[1939\u20131945 Star]]\n*[[Burma Star]]\n*[[War Medal 1939\u20131945]]\n\n== Later work and hobbies ==\n\nAfter leaving the army, he worked as managing director of a company manufacturing [[concrete]].<ref name=\"Spary\" />\n\nFor 64 years he organised the DWR's annual reunion.<ref name=\"Brown\" />\n\nMoore raced motorcycles competitively, wearing the number 23.<ref name=\"Hancocks\">{{cite web |last1=Hancocks |first1=Simon |title=Veteran NHS fundraiser Captain Tom Moore was also a motorcycle racer |url=https://www.visordown.com/news/general/veteran-nhs-fundraiser-captain-tom-moore-was-also-motorcycle-racer |website=Visordown |accessdate=17 April 2020 }}</ref> He rode a [[The Scott Motorcycle Company|Scott motorcycle]], winning several trophies.<ref name=\"Brown\" />\n\n== Tom's 100th Birthday Walk ==\n\nOn 6 April 2020, with his hundredth birthday approaching, Moore began a fundraising campaign to raise money for [[NHS Charities Together]], a group of charities supporting staff and volunteers caring for COVID-19 patients in the British public health services during the [[COVID-19 pandemic]]. He aimed to complete one hundred {{convert|25|m|yard|abbr=on}} laps of his garden, ten laps per day, with the help of a [[Walker (mobility)|walking frame]], branding the endeavour \"'''Tom's 100th Birthday Walk For The NHS'''\".<ref name=\"Spary\" /><ref name=\"Low\" /><ref name=\"BBC-52290976\">{{cite news |title=Army veteran's \u00a37m for NHS 'out of this world' |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-beds-bucks-herts-52290976 |work=BBC News |accessdate=15 April 2020 |date=15 April 2020}}</ref> \n\nThe initial \u00a31,000 goal having been realised on 10 April, the target was increased, first to \u00a35,000, and eventually to \u00a3500,000 as more people around the world became involved.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/nhs-100-birthday-walk-army-veteran-tom-moore-fundraise-a9463561.html |title=99-year-old army veteran raises more than \u00a31m for NHS with \u2018100th birthday walk\u2019 |date=14 April 2020 |work=The Independent |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref> Fund-raising soared exponentially when the British media publicised the endeavour. Moore, who joined [[Twitter]] in the same month, used the site to express joy over accumulating such a staggering amount of money for the NHS.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=CaptainTomMoore |number=1250418629218168833 |date=15 April 2020 |title=7 MILLION POUNDS!!!! The Great British public, your generosity is just incredible! THANK YOU!! }}</ref> \n\nThe [[JustGiving]] page for his walk reports that, as of 21:00 22 April 2020 (UTC), he had raised in excess of \u00a328.1<!-- please update the figure in two places and the date/ timestamp-->&nbsp;million,<ref name=\"JGTM\">{{cite web |title=Captain Tom Moore's 100th Birthday Walk for the NHS |url=https://www.justgiving.com/fundraising/tomswalkforthenhs |publisher=[[JustGiving]] |accessdate=22 April 2020 }}</ref> the largest-ever amount raised by a JustGiving campaign,<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://inews.co.uk/news/captain-tom-moore-just-giving-nhs-fundraiser-record-charity-2539792 |title=Captain Tom Moore, 99, breaks all time charity fundraising record with NHS walk |work=i News |publisher=JPIMedia |access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/uk-news/captain-tom-moore-completes-12m-18098819|title=Captain Tom Moore completes \u00a312m walk for NHS with honour guard|last=Shaw|first=Neil|date=2020-04-16|website=walesonline|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> beating the previous record of \u00a35.2&nbsp;million raised (partially posthumously) by [[Stephen Sutton]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Stephen's fundraising page |url=https://www.justgiving.com/fundraising/stephen-sutton-tct |website=JustGiving |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Butterworth\">{{cite news |last1=Butterworth |first1=Benjamin |title=Captain Tom Moore, 99, breaks all time charity fundraising record with NHS walk |url=https://inews.co.uk/news/captain-tom-moore-just-giving-nhs-fundraiser-record-charity-2539792 |accessdate=16 April 2020 |work=i News |publisher=JPIMedia}}</ref> More than 1.3 million individuals have donated.<ref name=\"JGTM\" />\n\nFunds raised by Moore are being spent on such things as well-being packs for National Health Service staff facilitating rest and recuperation rooms, devices to enable hospital patients to keep in contact with family members, and community groups who support patients once discharged from hospitals.<ref name=\"BBC-52278746\" /><ref name=\"BBC-52325713\">{{cite news |last1=Shepka |first1=Phil |last2=Lewis |first2=Katy |title=How will Captain Tom Moore's millions be spent? |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-beds-bucks-herts-52325713 |work=BBC News |accessdate=18 April 2020 |date=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nHe achieved his initial target of one hundred laps on the morning of 16 April, watched [[Social distancing measures related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|at a safe distance]] by a [[guard of honour]] from the [[1st Battalion, The Yorkshire Regiment|1st Battalion of the Yorkshire Regiment]],<ref name=\"Shaw\">{{cite news |last1=Shaw |first1=Neil |title=Captain Tom Moore completes \u00a312m walk for NHS with honour guard |url=https://www.hertfordshiremercury.co.uk/news/uk-world-news/captain-tom-moore-completes-12m-4050824 |work=HertsLive |date=16 April 2020}}</ref> into which the DWR were merged in 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.army.mod.uk/infantry/regiments/23987.aspx |title=The Yorkshire Regiment |publisher=[[Ministry of Defence]] |archivedate=27 May 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120527064813/http://www.army.mod.uk/infantry/regiments/23987.aspx }}</ref> He has said he will not stop, and aims to do a second hundred.<ref name=\"BBC-52278746\" />\n\nOn reaching the \u00a35&nbsp;million mark, Moore explained his motivation:<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/av/uk-52296313/coronavirus-army-veteran-tom-moore-finds-out-he-s-raised-5m-for-nhs |title=Army veteran, 99, finds out he's raised \u00a35m for NHS |work=BBC News |date=15 April 2020 |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|When we started off with this exercise we didn't anticipate we'd get anything near that sort of money. It's really amazing. All of them, from top to bottom, in the National Health Service, they deserve everything that we can possibly put in their place. They're all so brave. Because every morning or every night they're putting themselves into harm's way, and I think you've got to give them full marks for that effort. We're a little bit like having a war at the moment. But the doctors and the nurses, they're all on the front line, and all of us behind, we've got to supply them and keep them going with everything that they need, so that they can do their jobs even better than they're doing now.}}\n\n=== Charity recording ===\nTo mark Moore's 100th lap, the singer [[Michael Ball]] recorded a version of \"[[You'll Never Walk Alone]]\", with the NHS Voices of Care Choir, and featuring Moore's spoken words.<ref name=\"ITV\">{{cite news |title=Captain Tom Moore launches You'll Never Walk Alone charity single with Michael Ball |url=https://www.itv.com/news/2020-04-18/captain-tom-moore-launches-you-ll-never-walk-alone-charity-single-with-michael-ball/ |accessdate=18 April 2020 |work=ITV News }}</ref> The recording, released as a digital single by Decca Records,<ref name=\"OC-29504\">{{cite web |title=Captain Tom Moore scores UK's top trending song |url=https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/captain-tom-moore-and-michael-ball-walk-it-to-the-top-of-the-official-trending-chart__29504/ |publisher=Official Charts |accessdate=22 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref> went straight to number one in the United Kingdom's \"[[The Official Big Top 40]]\" chart, selling almost 36,000 copies in its first 48 hours,<ref name=\"ITVN-charts\">{{cite web |title=Captain Tom Moore and Michael Ball land UK number one with charity single |url=https://www.itv.com/news/anglia/2020-04-19/captain-tom-moore-and-michael-ball-land-uk-number-one-with-charity-single/ |website=ITV News |accessdate=22 April 2020 }}</ref> and was \"biggest trending song\" as measured by the [[Official Charts Company]].<ref name=\"OC-29504\" />\n\n=== Recognition ===\nMoore has given over 50 media interviews.<ref name=\"BBC-52333127\">{{cite news |title=Capt Tom 'speechless' as fundraising passes \u00a323m |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-beds-bucks-herts-52333127 |work=BBC News |accessdate=19 April 2020 |date=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 April, after Moore's 100th lap, a UK Government spokesman said:<ref name=\"Lovett\">{{cite news |last1=Lovett |first1=Samuel |title=UK death toll rises again as lockdown to be extended \u2013 follow live |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/health/coronavirus-news-live-update-latest-today-cases-deaths-lockdown-covid-19-a9467756.html#post-1187989853 |accessdate=16 April 2020 |work=The Independent |date=16 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\n{{quote|The Prime Minister will certainly be looking at ways to recognise Tom's heroic efforts.}}\n\nBy 20 April, more than 800,000 people had signed a petition calling for Moore to be knighted.<ref name=\"Patel\">{{cite news |last1=Patel |first1=Holly |title=Petition calling for Bedford's Captain Tom Moore to be knighted reaches over 800,000 signatures as fundraising total tops \u00a326million |url=https://www.bedfordtoday.co.uk/health/coronavirus/petition-calling-bedfords-captain-tom-moore-be-knighted-reaches-over-800000-signatures-fundraising-total-tops-ps26million-2543463 |work=Bedford Today |language=en}}</ref>\n\nBrigadier Andrew Jackson, colonel of the Yorkshire Regiment, described Moore as:<ref name=\"BBC-52340554\">{{cite web |title=Capt Tom to be guest of honour at hospital opening |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-york-north-yorkshire-52340554 |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=19 April 2020 |date=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|an absolute legend [from] an exceptional generation that are still an inspiration for our Yorkshire soldiers today.}}\n\nKeighley Town Council stated that they grant Moore the [[Freedom of the City|Freedom of Keighley]].<ref name=\"ITV-freedom\">{{cite news |title=Veteran Capt Tom Moore to be given freedom of Keighley after raising \u00a313m for NHS |url=https://www.itv.com/news/calendar/2020-04-16/veteran-capt-tom-moore-to-be-given-freedom-of-keighley-after-raising-13m-for-nhs/ |date=16 April 2020 |work=ITV News |accessdate=19 April 2020 }}</ref><ref name=\"BBC-52321262\">{{cite news |title=Prince William hails veteran's \u00a318m NHS fundraiser |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-beds-bucks-herts-52321262 |accessdate=17 April 2020 |work=BBC News |date=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n Moore was also guest of honour at, via a video link, and opened, the [[NHS Nightingale Hospital Yorkshire and the Humber]], in [[Harrogate]], on 21 April.<ref name=\"BBC-52340554\" /><ref name=\"BBC-52368691\">{{cite news |title=Capt Tom opens new NHS Nightingale hospital |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-york-north-yorkshire-52368691 |work=BBC News |accessdate=21 April 2020 |date=21 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Keighley Bus Company]] named one of their [[Optare Versa]] buses ''Captain Tom Moore'' on 20 April, and reprogrammed the electronic displays to show a \"Thank You Captain Tom\" message intermittently in between the vehicle's route and destination. A plaque inside the bus gives further information of Moore's life and fundraising.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=alextransdev |number=1252321237587628032 |date=20 April 2020 |title=And inside Captain Tom\u2019s bus...}}</ref> Other buses in the town, and across parent company [[Transdev Blazefield]], displayed an intermittent \"Thank You NHS\" message. Alex Hornby, chief executive of Transdev Blazefield, described the vehicle as the \"pride of the fleet\" in dedication to Moore, thanking him for his fundraising efforts.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=alextransdev |number=1252255561229504513 |date=20 April 2020 |title=The sun shines down on a bus called #CaptainTomMoore - the pride of the fleet in his home town of Keighley. }}</ref>\n\nA number of artists have painted portraits of Moore; some said they would gift the paintings to him.<ref name=\"ITV-paint\">{{cite news |title=Artists pay tribute to Bedfordshire's fundraising hero Captain Tom Moore |url=https://www.itv.com/news/anglia/2020-04-21/artists-pay-tribute-to-fundraising-hero-captain-tom-moore/ |work=ITV News |date=21 April 2020 |accessdate=21 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\n=== Similar fundraising efforts ===\nMoore's success inspired retired Welsh farmer Rhythwyn Evans to launch his own fundraising campaign<ref name=\"JGDE\">{{cite web|title=Her 91 dros COVID-19 Rhythwyn|url=https://www.justgiving.com/fundraising/david-evans186|quote=91st birthday challenge to support local NHS staff for Hywel Dda Health Charities because of their hard work during COVID-19|website=Just Giving|accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref> by walking 91 laps of his bungalow in [[Silian, Ceredigion|Silian]], [[Ceredigion]], on his 91st birthday on 18 April 2020. Evans said that his walk was \"inspired by and in solidarity with Captain Tom Moore\" and that he aimed to raise \u00a31,000 for his local health board \"to give something back to the community\", having lived to a \"ripe old age\". Evans completed the laps before 17:30 and quipped that his next aim was to get \"a good night's sleep!\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/18/welsh-farmer-doing-91-laps-of-bungalow-on-91st-birthday-for-nhs-coronavirus|title=Welsh farmer doing 91 laps of his bungalow on 91st birthday for NHS|work=The Guardian|date=18 April 2020 |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.itv.com/news/wales/2020-04-19/farmer-91-walks-91-laps-of-his-home-to-raise-funds-for-the-nhs/|title=Farmer, 91, walks 91 laps of his home to raise funds for the NHS|work=ITV News|date=19 April 2020 |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref> As of 00:00 on 22 April 2020 (UTC), Evans has raised over \u00a335,000.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.shropshirestar.com/news/uk-news/2020/04/18/grandfather-walks-91-laps-around-bungalow-on-91st-birthday-to-raise-cash-for-nhs/ |title=Grandfather walks 91 laps around bungalow on 91st birthday to raise cash for NHS|work=Shropshire Star|date=18 April 2020|accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/uk-wales-52333077/coronavirus-capt-tom-moore-inspires-91-year-old-s-walk-for-nhs |title=Coronavirus: Capt Tom Moore inspires 91-year-old's walk for NHS |work=BBC News |date=17 April 2020 |accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nSix-year-old Bristol boy Frank Mills, who has [[spina bifida]] and was only recently able to walk for the first time, aimed to raise \u00a399 by walking 10 metres outside his home.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-bristol-52354837|title=Coronavirus: Bristol boy with spina bifida raises thousands for NHS |work=BBC News |date=20 April 2020 |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref> As of 00:00 on 22 April 2020 (UTC), Mills has raised over \u00a3116,000 for NHS Charities Together.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.justgiving.com/fundraising/franksfinishlinefundraiser|title=Frank's finish line fundraiser|quote=I am walking 10 metres with my walking frame for NHS Charities Together because I have been inspired by Captain Tom Moore|website=Just Giving|accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\n\nMoore married Pamela in 1968,<ref name=\"Lavender\">{{cite news |last1=Lavender |first1=Jane |title=Captain Tom Moore had 'given up on love' before he met beloved late wife aged 50 |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/captain-tom-moore-given-up-21876074 |accessdate=16 April 2020 |work=The Mirror |date=16 April 2020}}</ref> and they had two daughters,<ref name=\"Lavender\" /> Lucy<ref name=\"BBC-52354991\">{{cite news |title=Captain Tom's daughter feels 'pain' of being apart |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-beds-bucks-herts-52354991 |work=BBC News |accessdate=20 April 2020 |date=20 April 2020}}</ref> and Hannah. Pamela died circa 2006.<ref name=\"Lavender\" /> Moore has lived with Hannah, her husband, and two grandchildren, in [[Marston Moretaine]], [[Bedfordshire]] since 2008.<ref name=\"BBC-52278746\" /> He also has two other grandchildren.<ref name=\"Brown\" /> In recent years he has received treatment from the NHS for skin cancer and, in 2018, a broken hip.<ref name=\"Brown\" /><ref name=\"Low\">{{cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/captain-tom-moore-99-walks-to-raise-millions-for-the-nhs-fzpn0cjfb|date=15 April 2020|title=Captain Tom Moore, 99, raises \u00a35m for NHS with 100th birthday walk|first=Valentine|last=Low|accessdate=15 April 2020|work=The Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newsweek.com/99-year-old-army-veteran-raises-2-million-charity-walking-his-backyard-1497742|title=99-year-old army veteran raises $2 million for charity by walking in his backyard|first=Khaleda | last=Rahman|date=14 April 2020|work=Newsweek|accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Spary\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/14/world/war-veteran-raises-millions-garden-scli-intl-gbr/index.html|title=War veteran, 99, raises \u00a36 million by walking laps of his garden|first=Sara |last=Spary|work=CNN|accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [https://www.justgiving.com/fundraising/tomswalkforthenhs Tom's Walk for the NHS (JustGiving)]\n* {{Twitter}}\n* {{YouTube|wUP-ty-Tj5E|You'll Never Walk Alone}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Moore, Tom}}\n\n[[Category:1920 births]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:British Army personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:Charity events in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Decca Records artists]]\n[[Category:Duke of Wellington's Regiment officers]]\n[[Category:English civil engineers]]\n[[Category:English motorcycle racers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Keighley]]\n[[Category:Royal Armoured Corps officers]]\n[[Category:Skin cancer survivors]]\n", "text_old": "<noinclude>{{User:RMCD bot/subject notice|1=Tom's 100th Birthday Walk For The NHS|2=Talk:Tom Moore (fundraiser)#Requested move 22 April 2020 }}\n</noinclude>{{short description|British Army Officer and fundraiser}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix   = [[Captain (British Army and Royal Marines)|Captain]]\n| name               = Tom Moore\n| image              = Captain Tom Moore fundraising walk.jpg\n| image_size         = \n| caption            = Moore during his fund-raising walk. He is wearing the [[1939\u20131945 Star]], [[Burma Star]], and [[War Medal 1939\u20131945]].\n| alt                = Moore wearing a blazer with regimental badge, regimental tie and three medals\n| birth_name         = Thomas Moore\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1920|4|30|df=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[Keighley]], [[West Riding of Yorkshire]], England\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| death_cause        = \n| education          = \n| alma mater         = \n| occupation         = {{Plainlist|\n* Army officer\n* Managing director \n}}\n| title              = \n| term               = \n| predecessor        = \n| successor          = \n| known_for          = {{Plainlist|\n* Second World War veteran\n* 2020 fundraising walk\n}}\n| alma_mater         = [[Keighley Grammar School]], West Yorkshire\n| boards             = \n| spouse             = \n| children           = 2\n| parents            = \n| relations          = \n| website            = {{URL|https://www.justgiving.com/fundraising/tomswalkforthenhs|Tom's Walk for the NHS (JustGiving)}}\n| module = {{Infobox military person |embed=yes\n   | allegiance  = {{GBR}}\n   |branch       = {{flagicon image|Flag of the British Army (1938-present).png}} [[British Army]]\n   |serviceyears = 1939\u20131946\n   |rank         = [[Captain (British Army and Royal Marines)|Captain]]\n   |unit         = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Duke of Wellington's Regiment]]\n* [[145th Regiment Royal Armoured Corps]]\n* [[146th Regiment Royal Armoured Corps]]\n}}\n   |commands     = \n   |battles           = {{tree list}}\n*[[World War II|Second World War]]\n**[[Burma campaign 1944\u201345|Burma Campaign]]\n***[[Battle of Ramree Island]]\n   |awards = \n  }}\n}}\n'''Thomas Moore''' (born 30 April 1920), informally known as '''Captain Tom''', is a former [[British Army]] officer known for his philanthropic work. Moore served in India and the [[Burma campaign]] during the [[Second World War]]. He later became an instructor in [[armoured warfare]]. After the war, he worked as managing director of a concrete company and was an avid motorcycle racer. On 6 April 2020, at the age of 99, he began to walk around his garden in aid of [[NHS Charities Together]] during the [[COVID-19 pandemic in the United Kingdom|COVID-19 pandemic]], with the goal of raising \u00a31,000 by his hundredth birthday. By 22 April he had raised over \u00a328.1<!-- please update the figure in two places and the date/timestamp -->&nbsp;million.\n\n== Early life and family ==\n\nMoore was born to Wilfred, one of a family of builders, in [[Keighley]], in the former [[West Riding of Yorkshire]], on 30 April 1920 and was raised in the town.<ref name=\"Brown\">{{cite news |last1=Brown |first1=Faye |title=The story behind the 99-year-old legend who raised \u00a314m for the NHS |url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/04/16/tom-moore-story-behind-14000000-nhs-legend-12565964/ |accessdate=17 April 2020 |work=Metro |date=16 April 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.strayfm.com/news/local-news/3082429/coronavirus-veteran-from-keighley-raises-over-2-million-for-nhs/|title=Coronavirus: Veteran from Keighley raises over \u00a32 MILLION for NHS|date=14 April 2020|website=Stray FM|accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2020/apr/14/war-veteran-99-raises-2m-for-nhs-by-walking-lengths-of-back-garden|title=War veteran, 99, raises \u00a36m for NHS by walking lengths of back garden|first=Jessica|last=Murray|date=15 April 2020|accessdate=15 April 2020|work=The Guardian}}</ref> He was educated at [[Keighley Grammar School]] and completed an apprenticeship in [[civil engineering]].<ref name=\"Nicholls\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2020/04/14/second-world-war-veteran-raises-2-million-nhs/ |title=Second World War veteran raises more than \u00a33m for NHS |first=Dominic |last=Nicholls |date=14 April 2020 |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=The Telegraph}}</ref>\n\n== Military career ==\n\nMoore  enlisted in the [[Duke of Wellington's Regiment#8th Battalion|8th Battalion, Duke of Wellington's Regiment]] (8&nbsp;DWR) at the beginning of the [[Second World War]], stationed in [[Cornwall]].<ref name=\"Brown\" /> He was selected for officer training in 1940,<ref name=\"Nicholls\" />  and attended an Officer Cadet Training Unit before being commissioned as a [[second lieutenant#United Kingdom & other Commonwealth countries|second lieutenant]] on 28&nbsp;June 1941.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=35218|date=11 July 1941|page=4057|supp=y}}</ref>\n\nMoore became a member of the [[Royal Armoured Corps]] on 22 October 1941 when his battalion, the 8&nbsp;DWR, became an armoured unit, designated as the [[145th Regiment Royal Armoured Corps]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=35740|date=9 October 1942|page=4432|supp=y}}</ref><ref name=\"Nicholls\"/> Later he was transferred to the 9th&nbsp;Battalion (9&nbsp;DWR) in India, which had also been redesignated as the [[146th Regiment Royal Armoured Corps]]. He was initially posted to [[Bombay]] and subsequently to [[Calcutta]].<ref name=\"Brown\" /> His regiment were equipped with [[M3 Lee]] tanks and participated in the [[Battle of Ramree Island]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Whiting |first1=Charles |last2=Taylor |first2=Eric |date=2008 |title=The Fighting Tykes: An Informal History of the Yorkshire Regiments in the Second World War |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=9kt-AwAAQBAJ&pg=PA132 |publisher=Pen & Sword Military |page=132 |isbn=978-1844156450}}</ref> He was promoted to war-substantive [[Lieutenant (British Army and Royal Marines)|lieutenant]] on 1&nbsp;October 1942 and to temporary [[Captain (British Army and Royal Marines)|captain]] on 11&nbsp;October 1944.<ref>{{cite book |date=1946 |title=The Quarterly Army List (August 1946 \u2013 Part I) |location=London |publisher=HM Stationery Office |isbn= |pages=385a |url=https://archive.org/details/armylistaugpart121946grea/page/398/mode/2up|archive-url=|archive-date=}}</ref>\n\nHe served in [[Arakan]] in western Burma and afterward in [[Sumatra]] after the [[Surrender of Japan|Japanese surrender]],<ref name=\"Nicholls\"/><ref name=\"BBC-52278746\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-beds-bucks-herts-52278746 |title=Army veteran, 99, raises \u00a34m for 'humbled' NHS |date=15 April 2020 |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=BBC News}}</ref> by which time he had risen to the rank of captain.<ref name=\"Nicholls\" /><ref name=\"BBC-52278746\"/> On his return to Britain he served as an instructor at the Armoured Fighting Vehicle School in [[Bovington Camp|Bovington]], Dorset.<ref name=\"Nicholls\"/><ref name=\"BBC-52278746\"/>\n\n=== Decorations ===\n\nFor his war service, Moore was awarded three medals:<ref name=\"ES\">{{cite news |title=War veteran, 99, hits \u00a314m for NHS as Hancock calls him an inspiration |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/uk/war-veteran-tom-moore-matt-hancock-9-million-nhs-a4415496.html |accessdate=17 April 2020 |work=Evening Standard |date=16 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\n*[[1939\u20131945 Star]]\n*[[Burma Star]]\n*[[War Medal 1939\u20131945]]\n\n== Later work and hobbies ==\n\nAfter leaving the army, he worked as managing director of a company manufacturing [[concrete]].<ref name=\"Spary\" />\n\nFor 64 years he organised the DWR's annual reunion.<ref name=\"Brown\" />\n\nMoore raced motorcycles competitively, wearing the number 23.<ref name=\"Hancocks\">{{cite web |last1=Hancocks |first1=Simon |title=Veteran NHS fundraiser Captain Tom Moore was also a motorcycle racer |url=https://www.visordown.com/news/general/veteran-nhs-fundraiser-captain-tom-moore-was-also-motorcycle-racer |website=Visordown |accessdate=17 April 2020 }}</ref> He rode a [[The Scott Motorcycle Company|Scott motorcycle]], winning several trophies.<ref name=\"Brown\" />\n\n== Tom's 100th Birthday Walk ==\n\nOn 6 April 2020, with his hundredth birthday approaching, Moore began a fundraising campaign to raise money for [[NHS Charities Together]], a group of charities supporting staff and volunteers caring for COVID-19 patients in the British public health services during the [[COVID-19 pandemic]]. He aimed to complete one hundred {{convert|25|m|yard|abbr=on}} laps of his garden, ten laps per day, with the help of a [[Walker (mobility)|walking frame]], branding the endeavour \"'''Tom's 100th Birthday Walk For The NHS'''\".<ref name=\"Spary\" /><ref name=\"Low\" /><ref name=\"BBC-52290976\">{{cite news |title=Army veteran's \u00a37m for NHS 'out of this world' |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-beds-bucks-herts-52290976 |work=BBC News |accessdate=15 April 2020 |date=15 April 2020}}</ref> \n\nThe initial \u00a31,000 goal having been realised on 10 April, the target was increased, first to \u00a35,000, and eventually to \u00a3500,000 as more people around the world became involved.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/nhs-100-birthday-walk-army-veteran-tom-moore-fundraise-a9463561.html |title=99-year-old army veteran raises more than \u00a31m for NHS with \u2018100th birthday walk\u2019 |date=14 April 2020 |work=The Independent |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref> Fund-raising soared exponentially when the British media publicised the endeavour. Moore, who joined [[Twitter]] in the same month, used the site to express joy over accumulating such a staggering amount of money for the NHS.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=CaptainTomMoore |number=1250418629218168833 |date=15 April 2020 |title=7 MILLION POUNDS!!!! The Great British public, your generosity is just incredible! THANK YOU!! }}</ref> \n\nThe [[JustGiving]] page for his walk reports that, as of 21:00 22 April 2020 (UTC), he had raised in excess of \u00a328.1<!-- please update the figure in two places and the date/ timestamp-->&nbsp;million,<ref name=\"JGTM\">{{cite web |title=Captain Tom Moore's 100th Birthday Walk for the NHS |url=https://www.justgiving.com/fundraising/tomswalkforthenhs |publisher=[[JustGiving]] |accessdate=22 April 2020 }}</ref> the largest-ever amount raised by a JustGiving campaign,<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://inews.co.uk/news/captain-tom-moore-just-giving-nhs-fundraiser-record-charity-2539792 |title=Captain Tom Moore, 99, breaks all time charity fundraising record with NHS walk |work=i News |publisher=JPIMedia |access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/uk-news/captain-tom-moore-completes-12m-18098819|title=Captain Tom Moore completes \u00a312m walk for NHS with honour guard|last=Shaw|first=Neil|date=2020-04-16|website=walesonline|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> beating the previous record of \u00a35.2&nbsp;million raised (partially posthumously) by [[Stephen Sutton]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Stephen's fundraising page |url=https://www.justgiving.com/fundraising/stephen-sutton-tct |website=JustGiving |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Butterworth\">{{cite news |last1=Butterworth |first1=Benjamin |title=Captain Tom Moore, 99, breaks all time charity fundraising record with NHS walk |url=https://inews.co.uk/news/captain-tom-moore-just-giving-nhs-fundraiser-record-charity-2539792 |accessdate=16 April 2020 |work=i News |publisher=JPIMedia}}</ref> More than 1.3 million individuals have donated.<ref name=\"JGTM\" />\n\nFunds raised by Moore are being spent on such things as well-being packs for National Health Service staff facilitating rest and recuperation rooms, devices to enable hospital patients to keep in contact with family members, and community groups who support patients once discharged from hospitals.<ref name=\"BBC-52278746\" /><ref name=\"BBC-52325713\">{{cite news |last1=Shepka |first1=Phil |last2=Lewis |first2=Katy |title=How will Captain Tom Moore's millions be spent? |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-beds-bucks-herts-52325713 |work=BBC News |accessdate=18 April 2020 |date=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nHe achieved his initial target of one hundred laps on the morning of 16 April, watched [[Social distancing measures related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|at a safe distance]] by a [[guard of honour]] from the [[1st Battalion, The Yorkshire Regiment|1st Battalion of the Yorkshire Regiment]],<ref name=\"Shaw\">{{cite news |last1=Shaw |first1=Neil |title=Captain Tom Moore completes \u00a312m walk for NHS with honour guard |url=https://www.hertfordshiremercury.co.uk/news/uk-world-news/captain-tom-moore-completes-12m-4050824 |work=HertsLive |date=16 April 2020}}</ref> into which the DWR were merged in 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.army.mod.uk/infantry/regiments/23987.aspx |title=The Yorkshire Regiment |publisher=[[Ministry of Defence]] |archivedate=27 May 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120527064813/http://www.army.mod.uk/infantry/regiments/23987.aspx }}</ref> He has said he will not stop, and aims to do a second hundred.<ref name=\"BBC-52278746\" />\n\nOn reaching the \u00a35&nbsp;million mark, Moore explained his motivation:<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/av/uk-52296313/coronavirus-army-veteran-tom-moore-finds-out-he-s-raised-5m-for-nhs |title=Army veteran, 99, finds out he's raised \u00a35m for NHS |work=BBC News |date=15 April 2020 |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|When we started off with this exercise we didn't anticipate we'd get anything near that sort of money. It's really amazing. All of them, from top to bottom, in the National Health Service, they deserve everything that we can possibly put in their place. They're all so brave. Because every morning or every night they're putting themselves into harm's way, and I think you've got to give them full marks for that effort. We're a little bit like having a war at the moment. But the doctors and the nurses, they're all on the front line, and all of us behind, we've got to supply them and keep them going with everything that they need, so that they can do their jobs even better than they're doing now.}}\n\n=== Charity recording ===\nTo mark Moore's 100th lap, the singer [[Michael Ball]] recorded a version of \"[[You'll Never Walk Alone]]\", with the NHS Voices of Care Choir, and featuring Moore's spoken words.<ref name=\"ITV\">{{cite news |title=Captain Tom Moore launches You'll Never Walk Alone charity single with Michael Ball |url=https://www.itv.com/news/2020-04-18/captain-tom-moore-launches-you-ll-never-walk-alone-charity-single-with-michael-ball/ |accessdate=18 April 2020 |work=ITV News }}</ref> The recording, released as a digital single by Decca Records,<ref name=\"OC-29504\">{{cite web |title=Captain Tom Moore scores UK's top trending song |url=https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/captain-tom-moore-and-michael-ball-walk-it-to-the-top-of-the-official-trending-chart__29504/ |publisher=Official Charts |accessdate=22 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref> went straight to number one in the United Kingdom's \"[[The Official Big Top 40]]\" chart, selling almost 36,000 copies in its first 48 hours,<ref name=\"ITVN-charts\">{{cite web |title=Captain Tom Moore and Michael Ball land UK number one with charity single |url=https://www.itv.com/news/anglia/2020-04-19/captain-tom-moore-and-michael-ball-land-uk-number-one-with-charity-single/ |website=ITV News |accessdate=22 April 2020 }}</ref> and was \"biggest trending song\" as measured by the [[Official Charts Company]].<ref name=\"OC-29504\" />\n\n=== Recognition ===\nMoore has given over 50 media interviews.<ref name=\"BBC-52333127\">{{cite news |title=Capt Tom 'speechless' as fundraising passes \u00a323m |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-beds-bucks-herts-52333127 |work=BBC News |accessdate=19 April 2020 |date=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 April, after Moore's 100th lap, a UK Government spokesman said:<ref name=\"Lovett\">{{cite news |last1=Lovett |first1=Samuel |title=UK death toll rises again as lockdown to be extended \u2013 follow live |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/health/coronavirus-news-live-update-latest-today-cases-deaths-lockdown-covid-19-a9467756.html#post-1187989853 |accessdate=16 April 2020 |work=The Independent |date=16 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\n{{quote|The Prime Minister will certainly be looking at ways to recognise Tom's heroic efforts.}}\n\nBy 20 April, more than 800,000 people had signed a petition calling for Moore to be knighted.<ref name=\"Patel\">{{cite news |last1=Patel |first1=Holly |title=Petition calling for Bedford's Captain Tom Moore to be knighted reaches over 800,000 signatures as fundraising total tops \u00a326million |url=https://www.bedfordtoday.co.uk/health/coronavirus/petition-calling-bedfords-captain-tom-moore-be-knighted-reaches-over-800000-signatures-fundraising-total-tops-ps26million-2543463 |work=Bedford Today |language=en}}</ref>\n\nBrigadier Andrew Jackson, colonel of the Yorkshire Regiment, described Moore as:<ref name=\"BBC-52340554\">{{cite web |title=Capt Tom to be guest of honour at hospital opening |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-york-north-yorkshire-52340554 |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=19 April 2020 |date=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|an absolute legend [from] an exceptional generation that are still an inspiration for our Yorkshire soldiers today.}}\n\nKeighley Town Council stated that they grant Moore the [[Freedom of the City|Freedom of Keighley]].<ref name=\"ITV-freedom\">{{cite news |title=Veteran Capt Tom Moore to be given freedom of Keighley after raising \u00a313m for NHS |url=https://www.itv.com/news/calendar/2020-04-16/veteran-capt-tom-moore-to-be-given-freedom-of-keighley-after-raising-13m-for-nhs/ |date=16 April 2020 |work=ITV News |accessdate=19 April 2020 }}</ref> Moore was also guest of honour at, via a video link, and opened, the [[NHS Nightingale Hospital Yorkshire and the Humber]], in [[Harrogate]], on 21 April.<ref name=\"BBC-52340554\" /><ref name=\"BBC-52368691\">{{cite news |title=Capt Tom opens new NHS Nightingale hospital |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-york-north-yorkshire-52368691 |work=BBC News |accessdate=21 April 2020 |date=21 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Keighley Bus Company]] named one of their [[Optare Versa]] buses ''Captain Tom Moore'' on 20 April, and reprogrammed the electronic displays to show a \"Thank You Captain Tom\" message intermittently in between the vehicle's route and destination. A plaque inside the bus gives further information of Moore's life and fundraising.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=alextransdev |number=1252321237587628032 |date=20 April 2020 |title=And inside Captain Tom\u2019s bus...}}</ref> Other buses in the town, and across parent company [[Transdev Blazefield]], displayed an intermittent \"Thank You NHS\" message. Alex Hornby, chief executive of Transdev Blazefield, described the vehicle as the \"pride of the fleet\" in dedication to Moore, thanking him for his fundraising efforts.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=alextransdev |number=1252255561229504513 |date=20 April 2020 |title=The sun shines down on a bus called #CaptainTomMoore - the pride of the fleet in his home town of Keighley. }}</ref>\n\nA number of artists have painted portraits of Moore; some said they would gift the paintings to him.<ref name=\"ITV-paint\">{{cite news |title=Artists pay tribute to Bedfordshire's fundraising hero Captain Tom Moore |url=https://www.itv.com/news/anglia/2020-04-21/artists-pay-tribute-to-fundraising-hero-captain-tom-moore/ |work=ITV News |date=21 April 2020 |accessdate=21 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\n=== Similar fundraising efforts ===\nMoore's success inspired retired Welsh farmer Rhythwyn Evans to launch his own fundraising campaign<ref name=\"JGDE\">{{cite web|title=Her 91 dros COVID-19 Rhythwyn|url=https://www.justgiving.com/fundraising/david-evans186|quote=91st birthday challenge to support local NHS staff for Hywel Dda Health Charities because of their hard work during COVID-19|website=Just Giving|accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref> by walking 91 laps of his bungalow in [[Silian, Ceredigion|Silian]], [[Ceredigion]], on his 91st birthday on 18 April 2020. Evans said that his walk was \"inspired by and in solidarity with Captain Tom Moore\" and that he aimed to raise \u00a31,000 for his local health board \"to give something back to the community\", having lived to a \"ripe old age\". Evans completed the laps before 17:30 and quipped that his next aim was to get \"a good night's sleep!\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/18/welsh-farmer-doing-91-laps-of-bungalow-on-91st-birthday-for-nhs-coronavirus|title=Welsh farmer doing 91 laps of his bungalow on 91st birthday for NHS|work=The Guardian|date=18 April 2020 |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.itv.com/news/wales/2020-04-19/farmer-91-walks-91-laps-of-his-home-to-raise-funds-for-the-nhs/|title=Farmer, 91, walks 91 laps of his home to raise funds for the NHS|work=ITV News|date=19 April 2020 |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref> As of 00:00 on 22 April 2020 (UTC), Evans has raised over \u00a335,000.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.shropshirestar.com/news/uk-news/2020/04/18/grandfather-walks-91-laps-around-bungalow-on-91st-birthday-to-raise-cash-for-nhs/ |title=Grandfather walks 91 laps around bungalow on 91st birthday to raise cash for NHS|work=Shropshire Star|date=18 April 2020|accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/uk-wales-52333077/coronavirus-capt-tom-moore-inspires-91-year-old-s-walk-for-nhs |title=Coronavirus: Capt Tom Moore inspires 91-year-old's walk for NHS |work=BBC News |date=17 April 2020 |accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nSix-year-old Bristol boy Frank Mills, who has [[spina bifida]] and was only recently able to walk for the first time, aimed to raise \u00a399 by walking 10 metres outside his home.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-bristol-52354837|title=Coronavirus: Bristol boy with spina bifida raises thousands for NHS |work=BBC News |date=20 April 2020 |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref> As of 00:00 on 22 April 2020 (UTC), Mills has raised over \u00a3116,000 for NHS Charities Together.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.justgiving.com/fundraising/franksfinishlinefundraiser|title=Frank's finish line fundraiser|quote=I am walking 10 metres with my walking frame for NHS Charities Together because I have been inspired by Captain Tom Moore|website=Just Giving|accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\n\nMoore married Pamela in 1968,<ref name=\"Lavender\">{{cite news |last1=Lavender |first1=Jane |title=Captain Tom Moore had 'given up on love' before he met beloved late wife aged 50 |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/captain-tom-moore-given-up-21876074 |accessdate=16 April 2020 |work=The Mirror |date=16 April 2020}}</ref> and they had two daughters,<ref name=\"Lavender\" /> Lucy<ref name=\"BBC-52354991\">{{cite news |title=Captain Tom's daughter feels 'pain' of being apart |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-beds-bucks-herts-52354991 |work=BBC News |accessdate=20 April 2020 |date=20 April 2020}}</ref> and Hannah. Pamela died circa 2006.<ref name=\"Lavender\" /> Moore has lived with Hannah, her husband, and two grandchildren, in [[Marston Moretaine]], [[Bedfordshire]] since 2008.<ref name=\"BBC-52278746\" /> He also has two other grandchildren.<ref name=\"Brown\" /> In recent years he has received treatment from the NHS for skin cancer and, in 2018, a broken hip.<ref name=\"Brown\" /><ref name=\"Low\">{{cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/captain-tom-moore-99-walks-to-raise-millions-for-the-nhs-fzpn0cjfb|date=15 April 2020|title=Captain Tom Moore, 99, raises \u00a35m for NHS with 100th birthday walk|first=Valentine|last=Low|accessdate=15 April 2020|work=The Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newsweek.com/99-year-old-army-veteran-raises-2-million-charity-walking-his-backyard-1497742|title=99-year-old army veteran raises $2 million for charity by walking in his backyard|first=Khaleda | last=Rahman|date=14 April 2020|work=Newsweek|accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Spary\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/14/world/war-veteran-raises-millions-garden-scli-intl-gbr/index.html|title=War veteran, 99, raises \u00a36 million by walking laps of his garden|first=Sara |last=Spary|work=CNN|accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [https://www.justgiving.com/fundraising/tomswalkforthenhs Tom's Walk for the NHS (JustGiving)]\n* {{Twitter}}\n* {{YouTube|wUP-ty-Tj5E|You'll Never Walk Alone}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Moore, Tom}}\n\n[[Category:1920 births]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:British Army personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:Charity events in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Decca Records artists]]\n[[Category:Duke of Wellington's Regiment officers]]\n[[Category:English civil engineers]]\n[[Category:English motorcycle racers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Keighley]]\n[[Category:Royal Armoured Corps officers]]\n[[Category:Skin cancer survivors]]\n", "name_user": "Pigsonthewing", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRecognition:restore ref", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tom_Moore_(fundraiser)"}
{"title_page": "Jimmy McGovern", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2015}}\n{{BLP sources|date=November 2010}}\n\n'''James Stanley McGovern''' (born September 1949 in Liverpool) is an English screenwriter and producer. He created the television series ''[[Cracker (UK TV series)|Cracker]]'' (1993\u20131995), a popular and critical success in the UK, for which he received two [[Edgar Award]]s from the [[Mystery Writers of America]]. He has also received recognition for ''[[Hillsborough (1996 film)|Hillsborough]]'', ''[[The Lakes (TV series)|The Lakes]],'' ''[[The Street (UK TV series)|The Street]]'' and ''[[Accused (2010 TV series)|Accused]]'', among others.\n\n==Early life==\nMcGovern was one of nine children born to working class Liverpool born parents, William McGovern and Jane Warner.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/cracker-writer-jimmy-mcgovern-says-5219049|title=Cracker writer Jimmy McGovern says he could have been IRA soldier if born in Ireland|publisher=Mirror|date=24 February 2015|accessdate=24 November 2015}}</ref> He had a stammer until the age of eight. He attended a Jesuit secondary school, [[St. Francis Xavier's College, Liverpool|St Francis Xavier's College]] in Liverpool. He taught for a time at Quarry Bank Secondary Comprehensive school, where he organised the end-of-school play.\n\n==Television writing career==\nIn 1982, McGovern started his TV career working on [[Channel 4]]'s soap opera ''[[Brookside]]''. He tackled many social issues in the course of the series, especially unemployment \u2013 which was at a post-war high at the time. In 1993, he created the drama serial ''[[Cracker (UK TV series)|Cracker]]'', about the work of a fictional criminal psychologist played by [[Robbie Coltrane]]. Made by [[Granada Television]] and screened on [[ITV Network|ITV]], the series was a critical and popular success, lasting until 1995. ''Cracker'' also aired in the [[United States]], on the [[A&E Network|Arts and Entertainment]] cable network. McGovern's writing earned him two [[Edgar Award]]s from the [[Mystery Writers of America]]. In 1997 he created ''[[The Lakes (TV series)|The Lakes]]'', a drama that shared ''Brookside's'' realist setting and reused themes from ''Cracker,'' such as gambling addiction. In 2006, he created the [[BBC One]] drama, ''[[The Street (UK TV series)|The Street]]''; its third and final season aired in 2009.\n\nMcGovern also wrote the script for the television [[docudrama]] ''[[Hillsborough (1996 film)|Hillsborough]]'' (1996), based on the events of the [[Hillsborough disaster|stadium disaster]] in 1989, which claimed the lives of 96 [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] fans at an [[FA Cup]] semi-final. Among the cast of this drama was [[Christopher Eccleston]], who also featured in ''Cracker'', along with former ''Brookside'' actor [[Ricky Tomlinson]]. In 2013, Eccleston said it was the most important work he'd ever done.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/liverpool-fc/liverpool-fc-news/2010/11/30/christopher-eccleston-says-jimmy-mcgovern-s-hillsborough-is-most-important-work-he-s-ever-done-100252-27739218/ |title=Christopher Eccleston says Jimmy McGovern\u2019s Hillsborough is most important work he's ever done |publisher=Liverpool Echo |date= |accessdate=2013-01-02}}</ref> Newspapers cited ''Hillsborough'' as a factor in a new inquiry set up in 1997.<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.screenonline.org.uk/tv/id/1052988/index.html | title= Hillsborough (1996) | work=Screenonline | accessdate=6 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nHis series ''[[Accused (2010 TV series)|Accused]]'' aired from 2010 to 2012 on BBC One. It followed a similar format to ''[[The Street (UK TV series)|The Street]]'' but with a crime component. The series' writers included McGovern, [[Danny Brocklehurst]], Alice Nutter and Shaun Duggan. It was produced by Sita Williams.{{citation needed|date=May 2016}}\n\nIn 2012, McGovern together with local Indigenous Australian writers from [[Sydney]], developed the Australian television drama series ''[[Redfern Now]]'', set among the [[Indigenous Australians]] of the Sydney suburb of [[Redfern, New South Wales|Redfern]]. The six-part series follows a similar format to ''Accused'', telling the stories of six inner-city households in one street whose lives are changed by a seemingly insignificant incident.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.screenaustralia.gov.au/funding/indigenous/SpecInit_redfernnow.aspx |title=Industry Support \u2013 Indigenous Programs |publisher=Screen Australia |date=2010-10-25 |accessdate=2013-01-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110422134105/http://www.screenaustralia.gov.au/funding/indigenous/SpecInit_RedfernNow.aspx |archivedate=22 April 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The series debuted on 1 November 2012, was produced by [[Blackfella Films]] and has been commissioned for a second series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2012/11/renewed-redfern-now.html |title=Renewed: Redfern Now |publisher=TV Tonight |date=2012-11-13 |accessdate=2013-01-02}}</ref>\n\n==Film writing==\nMcGovern wrote the screenplay for the 1994 drama, ''[[Priest (1994 film)|Priest]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/news/liverpool-news/jimmy-mcgovern-attends-fact-priest-3427304|title=Jimmy McGovern attends FACT Priest screening|last=Echo|first=Liverpool|date=2010-03-02|work=liverpoolecho|access-date=2017-05-12}}</ref>\n\n==Theatre==\nMcGovern wrote the book for the musical stage show ''[[King Cotton (play)|King Cotton]]'', which explores links between the [[Atlantic slave trade]] and [[Industrial Revolution|industrialisation]] in [[North West England]], as part of the [[Liverpool]] [[European Capital of Culture]] 2008. ''King Cotton'' premiered at [[the Lowry]] in September 2007 before moving to the [[Liverpool Empire Theatre|Liverpool Empire]].\n\n==Producer==\nIn 2009, McGovern was the executive producer on the BBC One miniseries ''[[Moving On (TV series)|Moving On]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2009/04_april/15/moving.shtml|title=BBC - Press Office - Moving On press pack: introduction|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Views==\nMcGovern has described cinema scriptwriters as being treated like hacks and forced to crank out countless drafts by successive producers. McGovern has openly criticised dramas such as ''[[Footballers' Wives]]'' lamenting the lack of quality, believable storytelling in the early 2000s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/4794478.stm|title=BBC NEWS - Entertainment - Cracker writer attacks ITV drama|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nHe believes that television directors are underrated. He says: \"I have worked twice with [[David Blair (director)|David Blair]]\" on ''The Lakes'' and ''The Street'', \"and I can tell you that he is the best there is. He can make a good project great... Why David hasn\u2019t won the acclaim he deserves is a mystery to me\".<ref name=ft.com-08-27>{{cite news|title=Seeing the director\u2019s point of view|date=2006-08-27|publisher=Financial Times|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/50cfb916-35e9-11db-b249-0000779e2340.html}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honours==\n* McGovern received two [[Edgar Awards]] for ''Cracker''.{{citation needed|date=May 2016}}\n* McGovern won an [[International Emmy]] for best drama series for ''The Street'' in 2010 and ''The Accused'' in 2011.{{citation needed|date=May 2016}}\n* McGovern won the [[BAFTA]] for Best Drama Writer in 2013 for the second series of ''The Accused''.{{citation needed|date=May 2016}}\n* Jimmy McGovern was recognised with the Lifetime Achievement award from the [[Royal Television Society]] for his body of work.<ref name=ibc.org>{{cite news|title=BBC, ITV and C4 recognised across the RTS Programme Awards|date=2018-03-23|publisher=IBC|url=https://www.ibc.org/production/bbc-scoops-17-rts-programme-awards-/2736.article}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Programme\n! Date\n! Channel\n! Notes\n|-\n| ''[[Brookside]]''\n| 1982\u201388\n| [[Channel 4]]\n| Writer of several episodes\n|-\n| ''[[Coronation Street]]''\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 1990\n| [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]\n| Episode #1.3115 (writer)\n|-\n| ''[[Screenplay (TV series)#Season 5|Screenplay]]''\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[BBC Two]]\n| Series 5, episode 11: \"Needle\" (writer)\n|-\n| ''Traitors''\n| TV film. Dramatisation of the [[Gunpowder Plot]] (later revisited in ''[[Gunpowder, Treason & Plot]]'') (writer)\n|-\n| ''[[El C.I.D.]]''\n| 1990\u201391\n| ITV\n| Writer of 3 episodes: \"A Proper Copper\", \"Christmas Spirit\" and \"Piece of Cake\"\n|-\n| ''The Play on One''\n| 1991\n| [[BBC One]]\n| 1 episode: \"Gas and Candles\" (writer)\n|-\n| ''[[Cracker (UK TV series)|Cracker]]''\n| 1993\u201396, 2006\n| ITV\n| Creator, and writer of several episodes and 1 special (2006)\n|-\n| ''[[Priest (1994 film)|Priest]]''\n| 1994\n| -\n| Film, starring [[Linus Roache]] (writer)\n|-\n| ''[[Hearts and Minds (1995 TV series)|Hearts and Minds]]''\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 1995\n| Channel 4\n| Writer of all 4 episodes\n|-\n| ''[[Go Now (film)|Go Now]]''\n| BBC One\n| TV film, starring [[Robert Carlyle]] and [[Juliet Aubrey]] (co-writer)\n|-\n| ''[[Hillsborough (1996 film)|Hillsborough]]''\n| 1996\n| [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]\n| TV film. Dramatised reconstruction of the events of the 1989 [[Hillsborough disaster]] (writer)\n|-\n| ''[[Cracker (American TV series)|Fitz]]''\n| 1997\n| [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] / ITV\n| 5 episodes (original teleplay)\n|-\n| ''[[The Lakes (TV series)|The Lakes]]''\n| 1997\u201399\n| BBC One\n| Creator, and writer of 10 episodes\n|-\n| ''Heart''\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 1999\n| -\n| Film, starring [[Saskia Reeves]] and [[Christopher Eccleston]] (writer)\n|-\n| ''[[Dockers (film)|Dockers]]''\n| Channel 4\n| TV film. Dramatisation of the [[Liverpool dockers' strike (1995\u201398)]] (co-writer)\n|-\n| ''[[Liam (film)|Liam]]''\n| 2000\n| -\n| Film, starring [[Ian Hart]] (writer)\n|-\n| ''[[Sunday (2002 film)|Sunday]]''\n| 2002\n| Channel 4\n| TV film. Based on the events of [[Bloody Sunday (Northern Ireland 1972)|Bloody Sunday]] (writer)\n|-\n| ''[[Gunpowder, Treason & Plot]]''\n| 2004\n| rowspan=\"5\"| BBC One\n| TV mini-series. Dramatisation of the lives of [[Mary, Queen of Scots]] and [[James VI and I|James I of England]] (writer)\n|-\n| ''[[The Street (UK TV series)|The Street]]''\n| 2006\u201309\n| Creator, and writer of 17 episodes\n|-\n| ''[[Moving On (TV_series)|Moving On]]''\n| 2009\u2013\n| Creator, and writer of several episodes\n|-\n| ''[[Accused (2010 TV series)|Accused]]''\n| 2010\u201312\n| 10 episodes (writer)\n|-\n| ''[[Common (film)|Common]]''\n| 2014\n| TV film, set in the north west of England and based on the UK's controversial [[Common purpose#Jurisdictions|joint enterprise]] law (writer)\n|-\n| ''[[Banished (TV series)|Banished]]''\n| 2015\n| BBC Two\n| TV mini-series. Creator, and writer of all 7 episodes\n|-\n| ''Defendant''\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2016\n| [[France 2|FR2]]\n| A French language remake of the British drama series ''[[Accused (2010 TV series)|Accused]]'' (creator)\n|-\n| ''[[Reg (BBC drama)|Reg]]''\n| rowspan=\"3\"| BBC One\n| TV film. Fact-based drama about the campaign by [[Reg Keys]] to obtain answers after the death of his son in the [[Iraq War]] (co-writer)\n|-\n| ''[[Broken (TV series)|Broken]]''\n| 2017\n| Writer/co-writer of all 6 episodes\n|-\n| ''Care''\n| 2018\n| TV film, starring [[Sheridan Smith]] (co-writer)\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|40em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|id=0569568|name=Jimmy McGovern}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080803224355/http://www.bafta.org/learning/webcasts/bafta-writers-in-conversation-with-jimmy-mcgovern-and-writers-from-the-street,382,BA.html In Conversation with Jimmy McGovern], [[BAFTA]] webcast\n* {{Screenonline name|id=510555|name=Jimmy McGovern biography}}\n* https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2010/nov/07/jimmy-mcgovern-tv-drama-irony\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McGovern, Jimmy}}\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English television writers]]\n[[Category:English people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:Edgar Award winners]]\n[[Category:People educated at Quarry Bank High School]]\n[[Category:English dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Showrunners]]\n[[Category:Writers from Liverpool]]\n[[Category:Male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:English male dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Cracker (British TV series)]]\n[[Category:Male television writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2015}}\n{{BLP sources|date=November 2010}}\n\n'''James Stanley McGovern''' (born September 1949 in Liverpool) is an English screenwriter and producer. He created the television series ''[[Cracker (UK TV series)|Cracker]]'' (1993\u20131995), a popular and critical success in the UK, for which he received two [[Edgar Award]]s from the [[Mystery Writers of America]]. He has also received recognition for ''[[Hillsborough (1996 film)|Hillsborough]]'', ''[[The Lakes (TV series)|The Lakes]],'' ''[[The Street (UK TV series)|The Street]]'' and ''[[Accused (2010 TV series)|Accused]]'', among others.\n\n==Early life==\nMcGovern was one of nine children born to working class Liverpool born parents, William McGovern and Jane Warner.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/cracker-writer-jimmy-mcgovern-says-5219049|title=Cracker writer Jimmy McGovern says he could have been IRA soldier if born in Ireland|publisher=Mirror|date=24 February 2015|accessdate=24 November 2015}}</ref> He had a stammer until the age of eight. He attended a Jesuit secondary school, [[St. Francis Xavier's College, Liverpool|St Francis Xavier's College]] in Liverpool. He taught for a time at Quarry Bank Secondary Comprehensive school, where he organised the end-of-school play.\n\n==Television writing career==\nIn 1982, McGovern started his TV career working on [[Channel 4]]'s soap opera ''[[Brookside]]''. He tackled many social issues in the course of the series, especially unemployment \u2013 which was at a post-war high at the time. In 1993, he created the drama serial ''[[Cracker (UK TV series)|Cracker]]'', about the work of a fictional criminal psychologist played by [[Robbie Coltrane]]. Made by [[Granada Television]] and screened on [[ITV Network|ITV]], the series was a critical and popular success, lasting until 1995. ''Cracker'' also aired in the [[United States]], on the [[A&E Network|Arts and Entertainment]] cable network. McGovern's writing earned him two [[Edgar Award]]s from the [[Mystery Writers of America]]. In 1997 he created ''[[The Lakes (TV series)|The Lakes]]'', a drama that shared ''Brookside's'' realist setting and reused themes from ''Cracker,'' such as gambling addiction. In 2006, he created the [[BBC One]] drama, ''[[The Street (UK TV series)|The Street]]''; its third and final season aired in 2009.\n\nMcGovern also wrote the script for the television [[docudrama]] ''[[Hillsborough (1996 film)|Hillsborough]]'' (1996), based on the events of the [[Hillsborough disaster|stadium disaster]] in 1989, which claimed the lives of 96 [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] fans at an [[FA Cup]] semi-final. Among the cast of this drama was [[Christopher Eccleston]], who also featured in ''Cracker'', along with former ''Brookside'' actor [[Ricky Tomlinson]]. In 2013, Eccleston said it was the most important work he'd ever done.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/liverpool-fc/liverpool-fc-news/2010/11/30/christopher-eccleston-says-jimmy-mcgovern-s-hillsborough-is-most-important-work-he-s-ever-done-100252-27739218/ |title=Christopher Eccleston says Jimmy McGovern\u2019s Hillsborough is most important work he's ever done |publisher=Liverpool Echo |date= |accessdate=2013-01-02}}</ref> Newspapers cited ''Hillsborough'' as a factor in a new inquiry set up in 1997.<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.screenonline.org.uk/tv/id/1052988/index.html | title= Hillsborough (1996) | work=Screenonline | accessdate=6 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nHis series ''[[Accused (2010 TV series)|Accused]]'' aired from 2010 to 2012 on BBC One. It followed a similar format to ''[[The Street (UK TV series)|The Street]]'' but with a crime component. The series' writers included McGovern, [[Danny Brocklehurst]], Alice Nutter and Shaun Duggan. It was produced by Sita Williams.{{citation needed|date=May 2016}}\n\nIn 2012, McGovern together with local Indigenous Australian writers from [[Sydney]], developed the Australian television drama series ''[[Redfern Now]]'', set among the [[Indigenous Australians]] of the Sydney suburb of [[Redfern, New South Wales|Redfern]]. The six-part series follows a similar format to ''Accused'', telling the stories of six inner-city households in one street whose lives are changed by a seemingly insignificant incident.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.screenaustralia.gov.au/funding/indigenous/SpecInit_redfernnow.aspx |title=Industry Support \u2013 Indigenous Programs |publisher=Screen Australia |date=2010-10-25 |accessdate=2013-01-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110422134105/http://www.screenaustralia.gov.au/funding/indigenous/SpecInit_RedfernNow.aspx |archivedate=22 April 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The series debuted on 1 November 2012, was produced by [[Blackfella Films]] and has been commissioned for a second series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2012/11/renewed-redfern-now.html |title=Renewed: Redfern Now |publisher=TV Tonight |date=2012-11-13 |accessdate=2013-01-02}}</ref>\n\n==Film writing==\nMcGovern wrote the screenplay for the 1994 drama, ''[[Priest (1994 film)|Priest]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/news/liverpool-news/jimmy-mcgovern-attends-fact-priest-3427304|title=Jimmy McGovern attends FACT Priest screening|last=Echo|first=Liverpool|date=2010-03-02|work=liverpoolecho|access-date=2017-05-12}}</ref>\n\n==Theatre==\nMcGovern wrote the book for the musical stage show ''[[King Cotton (play)|King Cotton]]'', which explores links between the [[Atlantic slave trade]] and [[Industrial Revolution|industrialisation]] in [[North West England]], as part of the [[Liverpool]] [[European Capital of Culture]] 2008. ''King Cotton'' premiered at [[the Lowry]] in September 2007 before moving to the [[Liverpool Empire Theatre|Liverpool Empire]].\n\n==Producer==\nIn 2009, McGovern was the executive producer on the BBC One miniseries ''[[Moving On (TV series)|Moving On]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2009/04_april/15/moving.shtml|title=BBC - Press Office - Moving On press pack: introduction|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Views==\nMcGovern has described cinema scriptwriters as being treated like hacks and forced to crank out countless drafts by successive producers. McGovern has openly criticised dramas such as ''[[Footballers' Wives]]'' lamenting the lack of quality, believable storytelling in the early 2000s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/4794478.stm|title=BBC NEWS - Entertainment - Cracker writer attacks ITV drama|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nHe believes that television directors are underrated. He says: \"I have worked twice with [[David Blair (director)|David Blair]]\" on ''The Lakes'' and ''The Street'', \"and I can tell you that he is the best there is. He can make a good project great... Why David hasn\u2019t won the acclaim he deserves is a mystery to me\".<ref name=ft.com-08-27>{{cite news|title=Seeing the director\u2019s point of view|date=2006-08-27|publisher=Financial Times|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/50cfb916-35e9-11db-b249-0000779e2340.html}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honours==\n* McGovern received two [[Edgar Awards]] for ''Cracker''.{{citation needed|date=May 2016}}\n* McGovern won an [[International Emmy]] for best drama series for ''The Street'' in 2010 and ''The Accused'' in 2011.{{citation needed|date=May 2016}}\n* McGovern won the [[BAFTA]] for Best Drama Writer in 2013 for the second series of ''The Accused''.{{citation needed|date=May 2016}}\n* Jimmy McGovern was recognised with the Lifetime Achievement award from the [[Royal Television Society]] for his body of work.<ref name=ibc.org>{{cite news|title=BBC, ITV and C4 recognised across the RTS Programme Awards|date=2018-03-23|publisher=IBC|url=https://www.ibc.org/production/bbc-scoops-17-rts-programme-awards-/2736.article}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Programme\n! Date\n! Channel\n! Notes\n|-\n| ''[[Brookside]]''\n| 1982\u201388\n| [[Channel 4]]\n| Writer of several episodes\n|-\n| ''[[Coronation Street]]''\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 1990\n| [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]\n| Episode #1.3115 (writer)\n|-\n| ''[[Screenplay (TV series)#Season 5|Screenplay]]''\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[BBC Two]]\n| Series 5, episode 11: \"Needle\" (writer)\n|-\n| ''Traitors''\n| TV film. Dramatisation of the [[Gunpowder Plot]] (later revisited in ''[[Gunpowder, Treason & Plot]]'') (writer)\n|-\n| ''[[El C.I.D.]]''\n| 1990\u201391\n| ITV\n| Writer of 3 episodes: \"A Proper Copper\", \"Christmas Spirit\" and \"Piece of Cake\"\n|-\n| ''The Play on One''\n| 1991\n| [[BBC One]]\n| 1 episode: \"Gas and Candles\" (writer)\n|-\n| ''[[Cracker (UK TV series)|Cracker]]''\n| 1993\u201396, 2006\n| ITV\n| Creator, and writer of several episodes and 1 special (2006)\n|-\n| ''[[Priest (1994 film)|Priest]]''\n| 1994\n| -\n| Film, starring [[Linus Roache]] (writer)\n|-\n| ''[[Hearts and Minds (1995 TV series)|Hearts and Minds]]''\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 1995\n| Channel 4\n| Writer of all 4 episodes\n|-\n| ''[[Go Now (film)|Go Now]]''\n| BBC One\n| TV film, starring [[Robert Carlyle]] and [[Juliet Aubrey]] (co-writer)\n|-\n| ''[[Hillsborough (1996 film)|Hillsborough]]''\n| 1996\n| [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]\n| TV film. Dramatised reconstruction of the events of the 1989 [[Hillsborough disaster]] (writer)\n|-\n| ''[[Cracker (American TV series)|Fitz]]''\n| 1997\n| [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] / ITV\n| 5 episodes (original teleplay)\n|-\n| ''[[The Lakes (TV series)|The Lakes]]''\n| 1997\u201399\n| BBC One\n| Creator, and writer of 10 episodes\n|-\n| ''Heart''\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 1999\n| -\n| Film, starring [[Saskia Reeves]] and [[Christopher Eccleston]] (writer)\n|-\n| ''[[Dockers (film)|Dockers]]''\n| Channel 4\n| TV film. Dramatisation of the [[Liverpool dockers' strike (1995\u201398)]] (co-writer)\n|-\n| ''[[Liam (film)|Liam]]''\n| 2000\n| -\n| Film, starring [[Ian Hart]] (writer)\n|-\n| ''[[Sunday (2002 film)|Sunday]]''\n| 2002\n| Channel 4\n| TV film. Based on the events of [[Bloody Sunday (Northern Ireland 1972)|Bloody Sunday]] (writer)\n|-\n| ''[[Gunpowder, Treason & Plot]]''\n| 2004\n| rowspan=\"5\"| BBC One\n| TV mini-series. Dramatisation of the lives of [[Mary, Queen of Scots]] and [[James VI and I|James I of England]] (writer)\n|-\n| ''[[The Street (UK TV series)|The Street]]''\n| 2006\u201309\n| Creator, and writer of 17 episodes\n|-\n| ''[[Moving On]]''\n| 2009\u2013\n| Creator, and writer of several episodes\n|-\n| ''[[Accused (2010 TV series)|Accused]]''\n| 2010\u201312\n| 10 episodes (writer)\n|-\n| ''[[Common (film)|Common]]''\n| 2014\n| TV film, set in the north west of England and based on the UK's controversial [[Common purpose#Jurisdictions|joint enterprise]] law (writer)\n|-\n| ''[[Banished (TV series)|Banished]]''\n| 2015\n| BBC Two\n| TV mini-series. Creator, and writer of all 7 episodes\n|-\n| ''Defendant''\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2016\n| [[France 2|FR2]]\n| A French language remake of the British drama series ''[[Accused (2010 TV series)|Accused]]'' (creator)\n|-\n| ''[[Reg (BBC drama)|Reg]]''\n| rowspan=\"3\"| BBC One\n| TV film. Fact-based drama about the campaign by [[Reg Keys]] to obtain answers after the death of his son in the [[Iraq War]] (co-writer)\n|-\n| ''[[Broken (TV series)|Broken]]''\n| 2017\n| Writer/co-writer of all 6 episodes\n|-\n| ''Care''\n| 2018\n| TV film, starring [[Sheridan Smith]] (co-writer)\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|40em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|id=0569568|name=Jimmy McGovern}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080803224355/http://www.bafta.org/learning/webcasts/bafta-writers-in-conversation-with-jimmy-mcgovern-and-writers-from-the-street,382,BA.html In Conversation with Jimmy McGovern], [[BAFTA]] webcast\n* {{Screenonline name|id=510555|name=Jimmy McGovern biography}}\n* https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2010/nov/07/jimmy-mcgovern-tv-drama-irony\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McGovern, Jimmy}}\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English television writers]]\n[[Category:English people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:Edgar Award winners]]\n[[Category:People educated at Quarry Bank High School]]\n[[Category:English dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Showrunners]]\n[[Category:Writers from Liverpool]]\n[[Category:Male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:English male dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Cracker (British TV series)]]\n[[Category:Male television writers]]\n", "name_user": "Kowtoo", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFilmography", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jimmy_McGovern"}
